<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Urges UN Involvement in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni urged the United Nations to support the faltering Lusaka
agreement on the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions on the DRC issue and Uganda's future role
in the region in CNN's Talk Show program in New York on Wednesday,
Museveni defended Uganda's military involvement in the DRC by
saying that it is to guarantee its border safety, to stop
recurrence of genocide in Rwanda and eastern DRC and thus achieve
national as well as regional stability.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Untied Nations should support the Lusaka
agreement logistically. He blamed the world body for being
insensitive to African problems previously. However, he noted,
the U.N. Security Council's special session on the DRC issue
shows that the U.N. is paying more attention to Africa.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the impact on economy of his country's
involvement in the DRC , Museveni said the economy has been
growing at a rate of over 6 percent per annum since 1986 and that
Uganda's military presence in the DRC did not affect the national
economy adversely.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old president also addressed issues of AIDS
orphans and the country's current priorities. He said Uganda
would try to contribute as much as possible to regional peace and
stability and create favorable environment for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Museveni is currently attending a week-long U.N. meeting on
the DRC issue. Leaders of countries involved in the DRC conflict
were also invited to the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
