<HEADLINE> Ugandan Hostages in Sudan to Be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government will
repatriate on Friday morning 21 Ugandans, including 18 children,
abducted by a Sudan-based Ugandan rebel group.
</P>
<P>
A total of 75 Ugandans who were held hostage in Sudan by
Uganda's Lord Resistance Army (LRA) will be released in batches in
the near future, the Sudanese News Agency quoted unnamed officials
as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation comes in line with the normalization process
between the two countries envisaged in an accord signed by Sudanese
President Omar al-Bashir and his Ugandan counterpart Yoweri
Museveni in Kenyan capital city Nairobi last December.
</P>
<P>
Sudan is committed to the implementation of the accord, the
Sudanese officials said, noting that the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) and the United States' Carter Center were cooperating
with Sudan in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Up to Tuesday, Sudan repatriated 57 Ugandans from the capital
city, Khartoum, and another eight from Goba, provincial capital of
Bahr El-Gazzal in southern Sudan, according to a UNCEF liaison
officer.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan government said that about 2,000 Ugandans are still held
captives in the hand of LRA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Sudan severed diplomatic relations in April 1995,
accusing each other of backing rebels operating on their respective
lands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
