<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Russia to Protect Chechen Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Thursday urged Russia to pay more attention to protecting
the rights and freedom of civilians in Chechnya while fighting
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who was here on a three-day official visit, met Thursday
with Yegor Stroyev, speaker of Russia's upper house, the
Federation Council, and Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State
Duma lower house of parliament, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
Stroyev, for his part, said the struggle against terrorism in
Chechnya must not be stopped halfway
</P>
<P>
He told reporters following the meeting with Annan that "if the
conflict in Chechnya is not carried through to the end a second
time, there will be further bloodshed."
</P>
<P>
"The conflict in the North Caucasus must not be escalated, but
the struggle against terrorism must not be halted," the Interfax
news agency quoted Stroyev as saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides Chechnya, Annan and Stroyev also discussed Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. secretary general agreed that it is impossible to
solve all problems in Chechnya at one go. He said, however, that
the conflict should be settled as soon as possible on the basis of
the U.N resolution concerning the struggle against terrorism,"
Stroyev said.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov, during this meeting with Annan, stressed that
Russian federal forces do not want to hurt civilians trapped in
Chechnya, but the militants blocked their flight and tried to use
them as human shields.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to meet Russian Acting President Vladimir
Putin and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He will also see Vyacheslav Trubnikov, director of the Russian
Foreign Intelligence Service, in a "strictly confidential" meeting
proposed by Annan, Interfax said, citing sources.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his Moscow talks, Annan will leave for Geneva to
chair talks on a settlement in Cyprus, Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
