<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEF President Calls for More Attention to Deal With Long-Term Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, SWITZERLAND, January 27 (Xinhua) -- President of the
World Economic Forum (WEF) Professor Kalus Schwab has warned the
world not to be complacent although the overall economic situation
this year is better than those in the previous years.
</P>
<P>
"There is one striking feature that differentiates this year's
Annual Meeting from the last ones: at this particular moment, we
are not confronted with any overwhelming crisis," Schwab said.
</P>
<P>
"You will recall that in 1999 we were deeply worried about the
global economic outlook; and two years ago, it was the Asian
crisis which was at the center of our attention. This year,
without such a crisis preoccupying our minds, we have even more
reasons to look at the truly important fundamental, long-term
challenges of our world at the beginning of the new millennium,"
he went on.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we are celebrating this month the longest lasting
expansion of the US economy since at least the mid-19th century.
Yes, the Asian crisis seems to be overcome. Yes, Europe is on the
verge of an economic boost, and even the Y2K bug turned out to be
just a small creeping creature," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the WEF founder stressed that, with all this good news,
the moment is appropriate to remember how vulnerable everything is,
humankind, ecology, economy, politics and so on. "Therefore, the
motto for this gathering should be let's fight complacency," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the problems of poverty, national,
religious and ideological conflicts, terrorism, nuclear
proliferation,pollution, corruption, and many others are items
left over business of the last century that must still figure on
the agenda of the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the most important challenge for the 21st century
is to bridge the paradox between the harsh business reality and
human and social values," he said. "This is not done by
superficially favouring either side or by simple cliches, but by
the daily practice of truly value based."
</P>
<P>
"The motto is fighting complacency, the focus is the new world
of the 21st century, but the criterion for success is our
capability to make a difference and live up to our mission of
being committed to improving the state of the world," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
