<HEADLINE> Angolan Displaced People Living in Desperate Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUANDA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Displaced Angolans in the north
region are living a desperate life without food, water, houses and
medicaments, while the officers of the government troops qualified
the military operation in the north front as "positive", official
news department said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The population living in the city of Maquela Do Zombo recently
liberated by the government troops from the rebels led by Jonas
Savimbi, which is located 254 kilometers north to the provincial
capital of Uige, are also racked by the rampant epidemic diseases,
including acute diarrhoea, malaria, tuberculosis, pneumonia,
anaemia and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
According to the municipal administrator Afonso Cuca, the
deteriorating humanitarian crisis is the unavoidable consequence
of the month-long destructive combat around and in the city.
</P>
<P>
Cuca said that the immediate task for his local government is
to improve the living conditions of the population, especially in
the field of health and education. Near the city close to the
Angolan-Democratic Republic of the Congolese border, six bridges
have been destroyed by the rebels, leaving the city isolated from
the outside world and standing without support.
</P>
<P>
But the Commander of the North Front Lieutenant-General Marcos
Correia Banza said on Thursday that the sweeping operation in the
north region have produced "positive" results, putting 14 of the
16 cities in the north Uige Province under the control of the
government troops. Before it was recaptured by the Armed Forces of
Angola (FAA), the city had been under the control of the Angolan
rebels for more than 16 months, said the source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
