<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Drops After Speculative Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan shilling Thursday
dropped to 69.88 against the U.S. dollar from last Friday's
nine-month high of 67.30.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya posted the shilling at an opening
commercial mean rate of 69.88 to the dollar from 69.43 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has played a pivotal role in stemming a
speculative wave of short covering that pushed the shilling off a
nine-month high of 67. 30 last Friday, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said 70.00 would provide strong support for the
shilling over the next few weeks unless there was a dramatic
announcement from an International Monetary Fund team, which is
in Kenya to discuss the possible resumption of a
205-million-dollar loan suspended in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Before the team arrived in the country the shilling moved up by
about eight percent over a week in anticipation of a favorable
announcement from the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
