<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Official Says Tanzanian Poverty Population Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The people living in
absolute poverty in Tanzania during the past 38 years has declined
from 63 percent to 42 percent, a UN official said this week.
</P>
<P>
Findings indicate there has been a steady decline in the
number of the poor since the country's independence, said the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) Resident Representative
Sally Fegan Wyles.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the achievement to good and relevant
social programs launched by the Tanzanian government, adding that
universal primary education, adult education, road construction,
health, water schemes had all been geared towards poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
However, Sally warned that more efforts are needed to
economically empower the Tanzanian people because the country is
facing problems brought by the fast increasing populations.
</P>
<P>
Official figures say in Tanzania, out of 700,000 school
leavers and drop-outs entering the labor market each year, only
40,000 of them get jobs in the formal sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
