<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Confederal Solution in Cyprus: Greek Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Greek Defense Minister
Akis Tsohatzopoulos here Thursday ruled out a confederal solution
in Cyprus and the possibility of giving some kind of recognition to
the breakaway regime in the northern area of the island.
</P>
<P>
Arriving at Larnaca airport, Tsohatzopoulos said "the
possibility of setting up a confederation in Cyprus cannot even be
up for discussion."
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos arrived here on a private visit to address a two-
day conference.
</P>
<P>
He said if Turkey wishes to be part of the world security
system, to accept United Nations decisions and walk down the path
towards Europe, it cannot insist on a confederation in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey invaded and occupied the northern third of the island after
an abortive coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the U.N. has been trying to bring the two
communities together in a bizonal bicommuunal federation, but all
efforts have so far failed.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side, backed by Turkey, insists the
recognition of their breakaway regime in northern Cyprus, which was
recognized only by Ankara, and the establishment of a confederation
of two states on the island.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Greek-Turkish ties, Tsohatzopoulos said "
improvement of these relations will go hand in hand with Turkey's
adjustment to EU (European Union) norms."
</P>
<P>
He said Greece continues to guarantee Cyprus' security to allow
efforts for its EU accession and a political settlement proceed in
a peaceful climate.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Cyprus, Tsohatzopoulos will have separate
meetings with local political party leaders and will meet with
President Glafcos Clerides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
