<HEADLINE> Belgium's Regularization Period Not to be Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Belgian Home Affairs Minister
Tony Duquesne has decided that the regularization period in this
country will not be extended, local media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The senate home affairs committee had asked the minister to
allow illegal immigrants to file an application for regularization
until midnight Sunday, but Mr. Duquesne said this would require a
change in Belgian law.
</P>
<P>
For nearly three weeks now, Belgium has been accepting requests
for regularization from illegal aliens who can show that they have
been staying in this country for some time.
</P>
<P>
The minister points to the extra staff that the municipalities
are receiving in order to process the requests. The senate
committee is worried about discrimination, because in some parts
of the country municipal services will be open all weekend.
Elsewhere offices close at noon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
So far, the number of illegal immigrants requesting
regularization has been far under expectations. In recent days
though municipalities across Belgium have been swamped by late
applications, the local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's anti-racism center suggests that in the big cities
municipal services will not be able to deal with the numbers.
</P>
</TEXT>
