<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Technology Pioneers to Meet in Davos for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAVOS, SWITZERLAND, January 27 (Xinhua) -- During this year's
annual meeting in Davos, the World Economic Forum (WEF) and
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu (DTT) will unveil a new program developed
especially for the world's fastest growing, most technologically
innovative companies, the WEF said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On January 31 and February 1, over 50 CEOs from the world's
leading pioneering technology companies, including Wipro Infotech
(India), Red Hat Software (USA), Africa Online (Kenya), TrustWorks
Systems (the Netherlands), DeCODE Genetics (Iceland), Autonomy (UK)
and Lernout &AMP;Hauspie (Belgium), will come together to discuss the
life lessons of managing rapid growth globally.
</P>
<P>
In a series of collaborative, informal meetings, they will
determine what key success factors are required to become a
technology pioneer, discuss common challenges and how to overcome
them, and share predictions of where technology is moving and how
it will impact the global economy. They will also meet such
veterans of the technological revolution as Yahoo!, Sun
Microsystems, Dell Computer Corporation, Novell and Vivendi.
</P>
<P>
"At a time of enormous technological change, it is important to
bring together companies that are shaping our future. It is key
for us to work together in engaging business in the global public
interest," commented WEF President and Founder Professor Klaus
Schwab, who is to host the awards dinner on January 31. "These
companies exemplify a new breed of corporate actors and we want to
help strengthen this community and incorporate it into our work."
</P>
<P>
The "Technology Pioneers" were selected according to two main
criteria: rate of growth and innovative power. Rate of growth is
based on three-year percentage revenue growth. The term "
innovative power" is based on in-house research and analysis from
the World Economic Forum, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu and industry
experts.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Thomas Doorley, III, Senior Partner at Deloitte Touche
Tohmatsu, will lead the discussion on the key success factors as
well as summarize the findings of the two-day event. "These
companies really will be the leaders of the future, and
understanding their success is crucial. All present have some
interesting stories to tell and valuable insights to share, and it
is essential that the WEF is behind this important initiative,"
Doorley said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu developed its annual "
Technology Fast 50 program"- a proprietary system for benchmarking
the fastest-growing technology companies using a common global
standard. The initial "Fast 50" ranking was developed for the US
market and grew into the "Technology Fast 500". More recently
Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu adapted this systematic method for other
countries around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
