<HEADLINE> Africa Regarded as Most Promising Market: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-two percent of
respondents have regarded African countries as the most promising
destination for new markets, a survey released on Thursday shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the Johannesburg Chamber of
Commerce &AMP; Industry (JCCI). All the respondents are engaged in
export business in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Spokesperson for the chamber Dorothy Lotter said East Africa
appeared to hold great promise with Tanzania featured as the
favorite new market in this region, followed by Mozambique, Kenya
and Uganda. Mauritius, Madagascar and Ethiopia were the other
promising countries named in the survey.
</P>
<P>
West Africa was indicated as the area with the second most
potential, with both Ghana and Nigeria getting the thumbs up from
exporters.
</P>
<P>
Southern African Development Community (SADC) members such as
Zambia, Botswana and Namibia were also featured as new
destinations for export markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 57 percent of respondents said that
their exports last year increased by an average of 28 percent
compared with 1998.
</P>
<P>
JCCI said the increase in exports was attributed mainly to
expanding market share and finding new markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
