<HEADLINE> Globalization Should Benefit Developing Countries: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will stress
at the annual World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, that
economic globalization should benefit the developing world,
President Thabo Mbeki said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Pretoria that the South African delegation
would highlight the impact of globalization on developing
countries, including those in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki and a number of Cabinet ministers were to leave for Davos
on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that direct foreign investment tended to
go to countries which were already developed, adding that ways had
to be found to address the issue of international capital flows.
</P>
<P>
"A critical matter is to find ways and means by which this
globalizing economy impacts positively on the challenge of
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Situations where rich countries were getting richer while the
poor ones got poorer should be avoided, he said.
</P>
<P>
"A process of globalization of that kind can only produce
disaster," Mbeki added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa will also convey a message of hope and confidence
to the forum so as to attract more investment, according to the
president.
</P>
<P>
"We will say that we are making good progress ... (and that)
the mood among our people in the country -- both black and white
-- is very good," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa had been asked to address matters such as
 development in Africa, and why people should invest in the
continent. Mbeki said: "We have to try and communicate the
views, concerns, hopes and aspirations of the peoples of our
continent."
</P>
<P>
"We will want to encourage a vote of confidence by the
international business community in South Africa," he said.
</P>
