<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Diesel Shortage to Affect Crops Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The diesel crisis lasting about
two weeks in Zimbabwe is expected to cut the production of some
crops by about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Soya beans have been heavily affected as we normally put the
crop in late January. We are now expecting a 50 percent or more
loss in production, " Director of the Indigenous Commercial
Farmers Union Nokwazi Moyo told the Zimbabwe News Agency on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said expected tobacco losses from fields to barns at present
stood at 20 percent but could be more if there were delays in
procuring fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
"The transportation from fields to barns is extremely critical.
 If a farmer is down by one day, there is a big loss and the barns
won't be able to catch up," he said.
</P>
<P>
Diesel is used as a substitute for coal during the drying of
the crop in the barn, and a prolonged shortage during a time when
harvesting has begun can result in decreased production and
reduced foreign currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said if electricity was rationed as threatened by the
Zimbabwe Electricity Supply Authority, farmers who depended on
irrigation would be further affected.
</P>
<P>
He said for those crops which were still being planted,
ploughing and seedbed preparation had been delayed or written off
in some places.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of diesel has also affected the horticultural
sector, preventing farmers from delivering their fresh produce to
the country's airports on time.
</P>
<P>
Director of Commercial Farmers Union David Hasluck said unless
the crisis was resolved by the end of this week, he foresees
substantial losses in foreign currency and in farmers' earnings.
</P>
<P>
In the 1999 marketing year, the sector earned about 100 million
U.S. dollars through the export of cut flowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Accident Kills 14 in Central Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 passengers were
killed and 11 others injured when a truck they were travelling in
careened off a bridge and plunged into a river in central Angola,
local government officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred near the Luime River in the central
province of Kuanza-sul on Wednesday when the passengers, most of
them itinerant merchants, were on their way to a rural market.
</P>
<P>
One of the victims died in a hospital at Cambambe, near the
scene, due to the lack of medicines, said a nurse of the hospital,
adding that the death toll could rise for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
Most Angolan hospitals have been suffering a chronic shortage
of medicines, as a result of the long-term civil war in the the
country.
</P>
<P>
Mechanical failures, bad state of the road and the excessive
cargo were to blame for the accident, said the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
