<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Revamp Diamond Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is planning to scrap the Diamond Act and replace it
with new legislation governing the local diamond industry
incorporated into a new Minerals Development Bill.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association on Thursday quoted an
official from the Department of Minerals and Energy Affairs as
saying that one of the Department's priorities for 2000 would be
to revamp the structure of the South African diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a gathering of Parliament's Committee on Mineral and
Energy Affairs, Ayanda Nkuhlu, secretary to the Minister of
Mineral and Energy Affairs, said : "In general the Department
will emerge with a more coherent strategy on diamonds, including
the future roles of the South African Diamond Board and the
Government Diamond Valuator."
</P>
<P>
Nkuhlu said the Department was currently overhauling both the
Minerals Act and the Diamond Act, to be replaced by a new Bill
that would be in line with the White Paper on Minerals.
</P>
<P>
Included in the new Bill, called the Minerals Development
Bill, would be the new provisions of the Diamond Act, legislation
on the transfer of mineral rights to the state, a new regulatory
regime for mining, and tax issues for the diamond and mining
industries.
</P>
<P>
The government also planned to lead a campaign to protect the
South African diamond industry from the growing threat of
international boycotts of diamonds as a result of diamonds linked
to support for rebels in areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We will lead a campaign to protect the industry from
potential disruption and destruction," he revealed.
</P>
<P>
Nkuhlu also said Diamond giant De Beers would also have to
improve its "corporate citizenship" in order to retain its
privileges.
</P>
<P>
 De Beers would have to "exhibit greater corporate citizenship
in South Africa, as well as greater initiative in developing the
manufacturing industry in Southern Africa, and in black economic
empowerment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since last year De Beers has been challenged by the newly
appointed government diamond valuator, DVIC, on a range of issues
including export pricing, its exemption from export duty, and its
decision to move a stock of diamonds to London in 1993, ahead of
the first democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
A commission of inquiry into the diamond industry late last
year urged a widespread revamp of the system, including the
Diamond Act, which allows De Beers and Trans Hex, South Africa's
second largest diamond producer, to export rough diamonds free of
export duty on the condition that clients in South Africa are
supplied with sufficient diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The commission was appointed by the government as the result
of a long series of disputes between De Beers and DVIC over the
export prices of diamonds to the Central Selling Organization
(CSO) in London. This resulted in delays in diamond exports of
more than 6 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
