<HEADLINE> British Judge to Rule on Pinochet Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A British judge will rule on
next Monday whether the Belgian government and six human rights
groups can go to court to seek access to medical tests on former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
The judge told Belgian government and the human rights groups,
who are trying to seek a judicial review of the British government
's decision to keep secret a medical report on Pinochet, that he
would made the decision next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw has repeatedly said he will not
release the independent doctors' report on the grounds of normal
patient-doctor confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
Staw said the report shows Pinochet, 84, is not fit to be
extradited to Spain to face charges of torture.
</P>
<P>
A Home Office lawyer told the court that Straw had released
sufficient information to enable interested parties to make their
submissions.
</P>
<P>
He said Straw had assured Pinochet that the results of the
medical tests would be given only to the Home Secretary and the
Crown Prosecution Service.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was arrested in a London hospital in October 1998 at
the request of a Spanish judge who wanted to try him on torture
charges. Belgium and France followed up with extradition requests
of their own.  
</P>
</TEXT>
