<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Company Per 13 People in HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) has one of the highest ratios of
companies to the population in the world with one company for
every 13 people, Gordon Jones, HKSAR's Registrar of Companies,
said today.
</P>
<P>
As at 1 January, 2000, there were 490,888 registered companies
in the HKSAR, of which 6,058 were public and 484,830 were private.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual dinner of the Hong Kong Institute of
Company Secretaries, Jones said the Companies Registry at present
takes only six working days on average to incorporate a company
and the time is expected to be further shortened.
</P>
<P>
"We envisage drastic streamlining of the incorporation process.
A specified form for application for incorporation will be
introduced and it will be possible to incorporate companies
electronically," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jones said there will be many momentous developments and
changes which would have a profound impact on the way the
Companies Registry operates.
</P>
<P>
"The Registry's expanded database will be made available on-
line early this year through the Companies Registry On-line Public
Search System," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Strategic Change Plan of the Companies Registry
envisages a fully electronic registry by 2005 with electronic
filing, processing and dissemination of information.
</P>
<P>
The Companies (Amendment) Bill 2000, which received its first
and adjourned second readings in the Legislative Council on
January 19, contains a number of reform measures, which, if
enacted, will "significantly help to simplify and streamline the
regulatory regime without lowering corporate governance standards,
" Jones said.
</P>
<P>
There would be a number of significant developments regarding
company law reform and corporate governance this year, said Jones.
</P>
<P>
These include the publication of the report by the Standing
Committee on Company Law Reform on the overall review of the
Companies Ordinance and a study by the Standing Committee of
corporate governance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
