<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dardanelles Bridge Project Off the Shelf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A plan to construct a bridge over
the Dardanelles, long shelved due to lack of funds, has come under
reconsideration, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The General Directorate of Roads has prepared for negotiations
with local and international construction companies to revitalize
the construction process of the 400 million U.S. dollar project.
</P>
<P>
The Bosporus and Dardanelles Straits are the strategic passage
between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean. Two bridges linking
the City of Istanbul's two parts of Europe and Asia were built in
1973 and 1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
A third bridge was needed to alleviate the heavy traffic across
the straits. The projected Dardanelles bridge will be the first
overpass above the sea lane.
</P>
<P>
The directorate announced that it favors the so-called build-
operate-transfer (BOT) system for the project.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Ministry of Housing and Public Works
have disclosed that a number of foreign construction firms, mainly
from Spain, Britain and Japan, have shown interest in the huge
project.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that they are currently concentrating on the
feasibility studies of two methods of raising the required funds
for the bridge, but they prefer the BOT model for, as they see it,
the system is more appropriate than foreign credit.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary negotiations with both local and foreign
contractors, who are included on the prospective bidders list, will
soon begin and a decision will be made subsequently on the choice
of the funding methods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
