<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak's Party Faces Criminal Probe over Fund- raising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Attorney General
Eliyakim Rubinstein ordered Thursday to open criminal investigation
against Prime Minister Ehud Barak's One Israel coalition over
alleged fund-raising violations in last year's elections.
</P>
<P>
Rubinstein took this action immediately after the State
Comptroller Eliezer Goldberg said that he believed Barak and his
One Israel ruling coalition are major violators of campaign
financing law in the 1999 elections, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Goldberg submitted his widely expected report on party
funding to Deputy Knesset (Parliament) Speaker Naomi Chazan, since
Speaker Avraham Burg is in Sweden to attend the international
conference on the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Barak and his close associates,
including his brother-in-law Doron Cohen and cabinet secretary
Yitzhak Herzog, used a variety of so-called non-profit
organizations (NPOs) to channel large sums of money from foreign
donors to fund Barak's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Goldberg asserted in his report that such campaign contributions
are illegal under the campaign financing law. Thus, he imposed One
Israel coalition a heavy fine of 13.7 million shekels (about 3.5
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
But some officials of the Labor Party, the backbone of the
coalition, argued that Barak only took advantage of a loophole in
the law at most and there is nothing wrong in that.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1973 Party Financing Law, money to fund election
campaigns must come from coffers. No foreign donations are
permitted, and Israeli individuals may only contribute no more than
1,700 shekels (about 430 dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel's electoral system changed in 1996, when a new
system of direct elections for the premiership was introduced. But
the wording of the campaign financing law was not changed to
address personal campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Thus both candidates for prime minister in 1996, Shimon Peres
and Benjamin Netanyahu, established NPOs to fund their campaigns.
In the 1999 elections, Barak and Netanyahu also use the same
tactics.
</P>
<P>
Labor party officials also pointed out that Rubinstein wrote in
a judicial review letter in 1996 that there was "a problem in the
interpretation of the (Party Financing) Law as to whether (it)
applied to the candidate for prime minister."
</P>
<P>
Although Rubinstein had changed his viewpoints on the subject
last August, some Labor officials said his judgement should not be
applied retroactively to the elections held in the spring last
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some political analysts worried that at a critical
point of Middle East peace process, any embarrassment in the fund-
raising saga will do damage to Barak's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also pointed out that President Ezer Weizman, who was
committed to supporting peace talks with Arab countries, also faces
already-launched criminal investigation over his alleged finance
improprieties with French millionaire Edouard Saroussi.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his wife Sarah are
also being investigated over suspicions that they illegally kept
gifts belonging to the state.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, for the first time in Israel's history, a president,
a prime minister and a former prime minister are facing criminal
investigations at the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
