<HEADLINE> Bomb Explosion Kills, Wounds 81 in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Eight people were killed and 73
others wounded on Thursday when a powerful bomb ripped through the
main post office in the northern Sri Lankan town of Vavuniya, the
Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"A claymore mine type bomb placed underneath the outgoing
foreign letter box had exploded around 11:20 a.m. (0520 GMT) today
" in Vavuniya, about 260 kilometers north the capital of Colombo,
said the ministry in a detailed statement on the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Of the eight dead persons, there are three civilians and three
soldiers while the other two have not been identified yet, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the wounded included 57 civilians, eight soldiers and
eight policemen.
</P>
<P>
Of the 73 wounded persons, except for 15, all others have been
evacuated to Anuradhapura Hospital for treatment, the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said earlier in a statement that the bomb
explosion had killed 10 persons and wounded 12 soldiers, 7 police
personnel and 20 civilians.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the soldiers were at the post office to send
money to their families in the south of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The bombing came despite tight security throughout the country
amid fears of more bomb attacks by the separatist Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels who are fighting for an
independent homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and
east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The bomb attacks have been the trademark of the LTTE rebels who
are blamed a series of suicide bomb attacks in recent weeks
against President Chandrika Kumaratunga and other senior officials.
</P>
