<HEADLINE> Appellate Court's Decision Not Yet Final: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Thursday that he will consult with government lawyers
on how to respond to a court decision prohibiting the spray-
painting of drug dealers' houses, Philippine News Agency (PNA)
said.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Estrada, who is in ILOILO city, Visayas, for
an inspection, as saying that the matter is not yet final, and
that the Presidential Palace still has the option to file a motion
for reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
"We will consult first with our presidential legal counsel,
Magdangal Elma. That's not final anyway. We can still file a
motion for reconsideration," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the country's Court of Appeals branded as
unconstitutional the spray painting campaign against drug dealers
in the city of Manila.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Alfredo Lim of the Department of Interior and Local
Government is heading the drive aimed at saving the youth from
falling prey to drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has declared an all-out war against the prohibited drug
trade which, he said, destroys the future of the country's young
people.
</P>
<P>
The president said his administration will undertake all
measures within the bounds of the law to stamp out the drug
scourge.
</P>
<P>
However, the court said the "scarlet letter" drive is violative
of one of the fundamental guarantees established in the
Constitution that all accused shall be presumed innocent until the
contrary is proved.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the appellate court said the appropriate and legal
course of action is to charge, arrest and prosecute suspected drug
traffickers. 
</P>
