<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Tense situation persisted
Thursday in the western Thai province of Ratchaburi as a result of
the hostage drama earlier this week, the official Thai News Agency
(TNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a group of 10 armed Myanmar ethnic rebels seized a
hospital in Ratchaburi town and took more than 500 medical staff,
patients and visitors hostage for 22 hours before Thai commandos
stormed the hospital, killing all the 10 rebels and rescuing all
the hostages on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Police in the provincial town, some 120 kilometers west of
Bangkok, said anonymous callers had made bomb threats against a
different hospital, a kindergarten and a department store on
Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, explosive experts searched these places found no bombs.
</P>
<P>
Parents rushed to take their children from schools which were
just opened Thursday after being closed for three days since the
hostage crisis began.
</P>
<P>
Authorities had ordered schools in Ratchaburi province to be
closed again until next Monday, according to TNA.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials and civilians have feared revenge attacks after
the Thai commandos killed the 10 rebels, some from the ethnic
Karen rebel group God's Army and the others from the so-called
Vigorous Burmese Student Warriors.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that a God's Army base in the Myanmar
side of the border has been overrun by the Myanmar government
troops. 
