<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Increase Defense Spending by 50 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting President
Vladimir Putin announced Thursday that government defense
contracts will be raised by 50 percent this year as compared with
1999.
</P>
<P>
Putin told a cabinet meeting that the developments in the
North Caucasus were not the only reason for the spending increase.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is much deeper," he said, "The army has been
underpaid for several years which has had a certain impact on
defense capability and in the socioeconomic sphere."
</P>
<P>
The chances of Russia having an effective modern army armed
with the latest weaponry have become questionable, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the potential of the military-industrial complex has
remained and that the personnel in the defense industry have been
preserved, although the belief that the defense industry will
become the locomotive of the economy did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
Putin called for a program of action to advance the military-
industrial complex, noting the 30 percent increase in the output
of high-tech civilian goods by the sector, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov, who is in charge of the
defense industry, said 80 percent more capital will go to arms
research and development in 2000.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that in 1999 defense contracts were paid for only
50-60 percent.
</P>
<P>
"But for the developments in Chechnya, we would have been able
to pay for the contracts 100 percent," Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
He said all arrears for the 1999 defense contracts would be
paid in the first quarter of this year and the arrears for the
1997-1998 contracts by the end of April. All debts that
accumulated in the 1990's would be paid in the next two-three
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
