<HEADLINE> Japan's Ruling Parties Approve Seat-Reduction Bill in Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives
Thursday approved a bill to reduce the number of proportional
representation seats in the lower house in a vote at a plenary
session that was boycotted by the opposition camp.
</P>
<P>
The lower house passed the bill which was backed by the ruling
coalition formed by the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the
Liberal Party LP), and the New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
Legislators from Japan's main opposition parties, the
Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the Japanese Communist Party (SDP)
, and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) stayed away from the Diet
(parliament) proceedings to protest what they called the
coalition's bulldozing of the bill.
</P>
<P>
After the approval of the bill, the opposition parties vowed to
continue to boycott all Diet sessions, including Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi's policy speech at Friday's plenary sessions in both
Diet chambers, and deliberations on the fiscal 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
The opposition bloc has been boycotting Diet sessions since
Wednesday morning, when the ruling parties held a debate on the
bill at a lower house committee, which passed the bill Wednesday
afternoon in the absence of opposition legislators.
</P>
<P>
If the all-out confrontation continues, Obuchi may opt to
dissolve the lower house for a general election, especially after
the enactment of the budget, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The controversial bill, which will cut 20 of the 200
proportional representation seats from the 500-seat lower chamber,
has been submitted to the House of Councilors (upper house).
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Party, which sees the reduction as part of its
political reform plan, has threatened to quit the ruling camp
unless the bill is enacted at the onset of the current Diet
session, which began on January 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Durable-Goods Orders Rise Sharply in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. orders for durable
goods soared in December, pushed by the biggest demand for
airplanes and other transportation equipment in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported Thursday that orders for
durable goods rose 4.1 percent last month, the biggest increase
since July, to a seasonally adjusted 212.9 billion dollars. That
followed a 1 percent gain in November.
</P>
<P>
For 1999, orders for durable goods, including items from air
conditioners to airplanes, jumped 7.1 percent, matching the
increase posted in 1997 and far surpassing 3.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In December, orders for transportation equipment rose a huge 16.
2 percent, led by strong demand for airplanes and aircraft parts,
although gains were reported across the board. The surge was the
largest increase since August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Transportation often is volatile from month to month because it
includes such big-ticket purchases as airplanes. Excluding
transportation, overall orders grew by 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Also, a 4.6 percent jump in orders for electronic and other
electrical equipment including semiconductors, circuit boards,
telecommunications equipment and home appliances also contributed
to the big gain in overall durable-goods orders in December.
</P>
<P>
However, orders for industrial machinery, including computers
and machine tools dropped 4.2 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that orders for primary metals, the category
including steel, fell 1.5 percent in December. This category has
been down four of the last five months.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a good signal of current
demand, also rose 0.7 percent in December, the seventh increase in
the last eight months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
