<HEADLINE> Bangkok Ready for Bidding 2008 Olympics: Deputy Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok is ready in terms of
finance and infrastructure to made a bid for the 29th Olympic
Games in 2008, Deputy Governor Theerachai Wuthitham was quoted by
local TV stations Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Theerachai said the city had already prepared financial and
infrastructure plans to make the city a potential candidate to
compete with Beijing, Osaka, Paris, Toronto, Istanbul, Seville,
and Havana for the staging of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet Tuesday approved the Olympic Committee of
Thailand (OCT)'s proposal of bidding for the 2008 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The government made a deal with Bangkok that both would pay the
82 million baht (2.19 million U.S. dollar) expenses required for
the advertising campaign before the five final candidate cities
are announced in September.
</P>
<P>
If selected as one of the finalists, the country would have to
spend another 441 million baht (11.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Both the government and the city would have to shoulder the
responsibility of raising the money, which would be spent on the
second promotion campaign until the winner is announced in July
2001.
</P>
<P>
Theerachai also said that the city is expected to spend five
billion baht (133.8 million dollars) a year to prepare for the
Olympics should it be granted the right to host the Games.
</P>
<P>
He added that Bangkok is developing its infrastructure and
transportation system, including the construction of elevated
roads and subway trains.
</P>
<P>
Theerachai emphasized that the large amount spent on the
bidding for the Games would not be wasted even if the country did
not win the right because Thailand will benefit from a recovered
foreign investor confidence as a result of the bidding and a
boosted local tourism industry thanks to the first-stage
advertising campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
