<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts to Protect Rights of Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's top judge said here
today that the courts in the country will strongly support news
organizations and journalists in playing their social supervisory
role and protect their legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
In China both courts and the media are working for the rule of
law, and they should support and cooperate with each other, said
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court, at a meeting
with executives of the country's leading news organizations based
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Xiao promised that the courts will facilitate journalists in
their covering of court proceedings and protection their
legitimate rights when they are framed or even assaulted. In cases
when news organizations are sued by those involved news stories,
courts will try to resort to mediation to legitimately protect the
reputation of the news organizations concerned.
</P>
<P>
Xiao said he is willing to improve information exchanges with
news organizations.  
</P>
