Wednesday night, on the eve of the release of the state
comptroller's report on the non-profit organizations that assisted
the parties and the candidates for prime minister in the 1999
election by allegedly tunneling illegal fund.
</P>
<P>
Copies of the report circulated freely Wednesday among
parliamentarians from the coalition and the opposition as well as
in government ministries, but its content is barred to be published
by media until 1 P.M. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both the ruling One Israel coalition and the opposition Likud
Party professed to be satisfied with the document's contents.
However, the Likud contends there will be no choice but to launch a
criminal investigation against those involved, perhaps even against
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
