<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dardanelles Overpass Project in Turkey Under Reconsideration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The government of Turkey is
reconsidering a plan to build the first overpass over the
Dardanelles Strait, which was put on the shelf due to a lack of
funds, the Anatolia News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The General Directorate of Roads has been preparing for
negotiations with local and international construction companies to
revitalize the construction process of the 400-million-U.S.-dollar
project.
</P>
<P>
The directorate announced that it favors the build-operate-
transfer (BOT) system for the project, which is seen as more
appropriate than foreign credit.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign construction firms, mainly from Spain,
Britain and Japan, have shown interest in the mega project, said
officials with the Ministry of Public Works and Housing.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is currently working on the feasibility studies of
the two methods of raising the required funds for the bridge.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary negotiations with local and foreign contractors,
which are listed as prospective bidders, will soon begin and a
decision will be made concerning the fund-raising methods.
</P>
<P>
The Bosporus and Dardanelles Straits are two strategic passages
between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean. Two bridges linking
Istanbul's European and Asian parts were built in 1973 and 1998
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The projected Dardanelles bridge will be the first overpass
above the sea lane, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Launches Clean-Up Following Oil Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
has mobilized a 100-strong team of municipality workers to clean up
coastal areas of Abu Dhabi polluted by the oil slick from the ship
Al Jazya 1 which sank on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Oil which had leaked from the Honduran-flagged ship was found to
have come ashore on the beaches of some small islands in the
emirate, local media reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The situation on the beaches will be assessed before a decision
can be made as to whether a specialist private company should be
brought in to help the clean-up efforts, Hamad Abdul Rahman Al-
Madfa, chairman of the United Arab Emirates Federal Environmental
Agency(FEA), told the Gulf News daily.
</P>
<P>
There are reports that oiled waders have been discovered on the
affected islands, and officials have also expressed fears that the
clean-up operation can have a damaging effect on historic and
archaeological sites in the oil-affected area, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The ship, run by an Abu Dhabi-based company, sank about 11.3
kilometers off east of Abu Dhabi coast while sailing from Abu Dhabi
to Somalia laden with 980 tons of heavy fuel.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed specialist company has begun to pump out the
remaining oil on the vessel, refloat the ship and tow it to port
under official authorization, the FEA chairman said.
</P>
<P>
At least 200-300 tons of oil had spilled from the ship before
the leaks were fully closed.
</P>
<P>
Coast guard officials suggested that overload and bad weather
might be the cause of the capsize of the ship.
</P>
<P>
Other officials suggest that the ill-fated tanker was operating
illegally in UAE waters when it sank.
</P>
<P>
The eight crew members and the captain of the vessel have been
safely rescued and are currently in police custody, Gulf News said.
The crew are a mixture of Iraqis, Indians, Bangladeshis and
Tanzanians, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
