<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Party Officials to Cross Buffer Zone for Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Parties of Greek and Turkish
Cypriots will meet on each other's home ground for the first time
next month, the Cyrus Mail newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One meeting will be held on the Greek Cypriot side on February
16 and the other on the Turkish Cypriot side on February 17.
</P>
<P>
Deputies to take part in the meeting from the Greek Cypriot side
include leader of the governing Democratic Rally party Nicos
Anastassiades, Andreas Phillipou from the communist AKEL party,
Stathis Kittis from Democratic Party, Doros Theodorou from the
socialist EDEK party and Androulla Vassiliou from the United
Democrats party.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders of the two sides held meetings on and off at
the U.N.-controlled Ledra Palace, at buffer zone in central
Nicosia, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Previous meetings between the parties were held at the Ledra
Palace under the auspices of the Czech and Slovak embassies, but
ground to a halt after 1997, when the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash cut off bicommunal contact in retaliation for the European
Union's rejection of Turkey's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
