<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Teachers' Strike Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A 12-day-long strike by
Israeli teachers is set to end after representatives from the
teachers' union reached an agreement with the Finance Ministry and
the Education Ministry over pay rise Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed after an overnight meeting among the three
sides, offered a five-percent compensation for erosion of their
wages between 1993 and 1995, according to an Israel Radio report.
</P>
<P>
Kindergartens, elementary schools and most junior high schools,
which have been closed since January 16 as a result of the strike,
are set to open Friday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Some 85,000 teachers have taken part in the strike, which has
affected about one million students.
</P>
<P>
The teachers had demanded a 15 percent compensation for erosion
of their salaries since 1994, or a total package of 1.8 billion
shekels(about 450 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Treasury, however, had stuck to its plan for a 1.2 percent
increase plus a one-time payment of 900 shekels (about 225 U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
