<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Israeli Report on Peace Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
denied an Israeli newspaper report that Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat had presented a proposal on the final peace with Israel
during his meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Israeli daily Ha'aretz claimed that PNA had
proposed to accept the Israeli annexation of Jewish settlements in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange for areas located within
the Green Line.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had asserted to Clinton on several occasions that the
building of settlements is illegitimate and poses a major obstacle
to peace-making, said the PNA official during an exclusive
interview with the Palestinian daily Alqods printed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He also affirmed that the PNA is determined to establish an
independent Palestinian state on all territories occupied by Israel
during the two Middle East wars, including East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian chief negotiator in the final-status
talks Yasser Abed Rabbo dismissed the report as "Israeli test
balloons."
</P>
<P>
"I have never offered such proposals" and what was published in
Ha'aretz "is fully untrue and entirely fabricated," said the
negotiating chief.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Abed Rabbo agreed on Wednesday evening
with his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran in west Jerusalem that
marathon negotiations should start next Sunday and last until
February 13 to reach a framework agreement on the final-status
issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed that such negotiations should be
conducted extensively and profoundly in order to meet the February
13 deadline under the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum signed last
September.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side wanted the negotiations to be held in
Washington in early February, an idea rejected by the Israeli side
for fear of any American intervention in the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
