<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia for More Stable Global Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Thursday
Asian countries should continue to pursue their call for an
improved and more stable global financial system that would ensure
a safer world for cross-border flows.
</P>
<P>
"We urge Southeast Asian Central Bank Governors Conference
economies to persist in efforts to ensure reforms to the
international financial architecture," Malaysian Finance Minister
Daim Zainuddin said while officiating the 25th Southeast Asian
Central Bank Governors Conference (SEACEN) here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that these reforms are necessary given the fundamental
weaknesses of the free market system, the inherent instability of
the international financial system and the need to ensure that all
economies are protected from the manipulative activities of
currency traders and highly leveraged hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
The minister regretted that not much progress has been made in
implementing the reforms because much of the debate on these
issues continue to be dominated by a small and closed group of
countries, namely, the group of seven industrialized (G-7)
countries.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need to ensure that the views and concerns of small
economies are given due consideration as these economies are more
vulnerable to the destabilizing effects of massive and volatile
short term capital flows," Daim said.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, I believe that SEACEN as a group can play an
important role in mobilizing the support of developing countries,
as a common stance will strengthen our influence on decisions on
international financial architecture issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said crisis-hit Asian countries cannot be overly dependent
on the developed nations as a source of recovery and growth given
the prevailing uncertainty in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure uninterrupted and steady growth, we need to prepare
to be economically more resilient to better manage the vagaries of
external developments," the Malaysian minister said.
</P>
<P>
The countries could begin by building regional economic
resilience to enhance their efforts to effectively manage economic
uncertainty by expanding the scope and pace of regional
cooperation, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
