<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Krung Bank to Bring NPLs Down to 40 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Krung Thai Bank, Thailand's
state-owned commercial bank, expects to restructure 170 billion
baht(4.55 billion U.S. dollars) in loan this year, bring the non-
performing loans (NPLs) down to 40 percent of total loans, the
Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the bank, the second largest commercial bank in
Thailand,resolved problems for borrowings totaling 127 billion
baht (3.39 billion dollars), exceeding its target by 20 percent,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Post quoted Dusit Tengniyom, the bank's senior
executive vice-president, as saying that the bank restructured
loans for more than 21,000 customers in 1999, adding that the
greatest progress was made in the fourth quarter when 71.6 billion
baht (1.91 billion dollars) in loans were restructured and the
bank's NPLs were at 57 percent of total loans, or 590 billion baht
(15.7 billion dollars) at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Another 780 customers with loans of 13.65 billion baht (365.2
million dollars) are ready to sign restructuring contracts,
according to the bank official.
</P>
<P>
If restructuring goes according to plan, the bank's NPLs could
fall to 40 percent of total outstanding loans by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Plans to set up an asset management company are likely to
further bring down the NPL level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
