<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pensions in New Zealand Raised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Superannuitants are to
receive a big pay rise after the New Zealand government made a
formal announcement of increasing pensions here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, a married couple will receive another 21.
42 NZ dollars (about 11 U.S. dollars) a week and single people
approximately 12.5 NZ dollars (about 6.4 U.S. dollars) from April
1.
</P>
<P>
While making the announcement, New Zealand Finance Minister
Michael Cullen said the increase fulfills election pledges from
the Labor Party and its coalition partner the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
As of April 1, the married rate for New Zealand Superannuation
and for the Veterans' Pension will increase from 325.58 NZ dollars
(166 U.S. dollars) to 347 NZ dollars (177 U.S. dollars) a week.
The single living alone rate and the single sharing rate are
calculated at 65 percent and 60 percent of the married rate.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the new government will spend an extra 700
million NZ dollars (357 million U.S. dollars) on state pensions
over the next four years. Extra government spending will be funded
by higher taxes for people earning more than 60,000 NZ dollars (30,
600 U.S. dollars) a year and an expected economic recovery
boosting tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The increase will please superannuitants angry about the former
government last year lowering the "floor" for calculating the
married, or base rate. Under that policy, the base rate was
gradually dropping from 65 percent of the average wage for a
normal working week to 60 percent. Pensions would be adjusted only
for inflation until the floor was reached.
</P>
<P>
The base rate is currently 62.6 percent of the average wage and
would have fallen further on April 1. However, after the new
government's policy, that percentage will rise to about 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
"For as long as it is over 65 percent, it will be adjusted for
inflation only. But it will never be allowed to sink below 65
percent again under this government. That is our undertaking to
the New Zealand public," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Foreign Policy to Face Challenge in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign policy in
the year 2000 will still face challenges, but enjoy full support
from the international community in dealing with domestic problems,
Indonesian Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Indonesian government had also taken
steps in a bid to strengthen its bilateral ties with countries of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nation (ASEAN) and some other
Asian countries such as China, India and Japan.
</P>
<P>
These countries will play a significant role, besides Western
countries, in creating a fair world economic order, the minister
said in an annual press gathering to review Indonesia's foreign
policy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The minister predicted that the development of the world
politics in 2000 would feature democratization, good governance
and environment issues.
</P>
<P>
"And the relationship among countries (in the 21st century)
would show more interdependence," Shihab said, adding that
Indonesia's ties with Middle East countries would be better and
better particularly in economic and trade sectors in the new
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
