<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to See GDP Growth in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Financial services firm
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said Thursday that Malaysia's gross
domestic product (GDP) is forecast to grow between 5.5 percent and
6.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy is also forecast to perform well with its
trade accounts of more than one-and-a half times its entire
economy,Faisal Mian, its London-based vice-president for fixed
income sovereign research, said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is in line with the rosy outlook of the global
economy which Morgan Stanley anticipated would grow by 4 percent
this year while the World Trade Organization (WTO) procedure to
promote trade is expected to go well, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said emerging market investors are now looking again at Asia
in allocating their capital portfolio and Malaysia seems to be one
of their favorite stories.
</P>
<P>
He said the most important point for fixed income investors is
stability and all doubts have now been answered with the election
already out of the way in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Stanley anticipated two rating agencies, Moody's and
Standard &AMP; Poor's, to upgrade Malaysia's sovereign debt rating
within this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mian, together with Oliver Jory, executive director for debt
capital markets of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter Asia, is here on a
fact-finding mission, leading a delegation of 15-fixed income
investors from the United States, Britain and the Asia Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Mian said both rating agencies would take time to make their
decision but an upgrade on Malaysia's debt ceiling following its
better liquidity and solvency ratio is pretty certain.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's debt currently stands at 43 billion U.S. dollars,
its reserves in excess of 31 billion dollars and its exports in
the range of 87 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jory meanwhile said at the press conference that there is
tremendous demand for Malaysia's fixed assets as Malaysian
sovereign and corporate bonds performed well in the international
market last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that therefore there are lots of opportunities for
Malaysia and the corporate sector to tap the international bond
market this year, especially euro bonds.
</P>
<P>
The need for Malaysia to tap the international capital market
is not driven by requirement but opportunities to allow
international investors to focus on the development in Malaysia
and put the nation under the spotlight, Jory said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
