<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Leader Urges to Improve School Teachers' Welfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Thursday issued a series of directives aimed at improving
the plight of the country's public school teachers, the
presidential palace said.
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement said Estrada also lauded a senate
initiative to undertake a comprehensive research project aimed at
promoting the public school teachers' welfare.
</P>
<P>
"The senate project, a first attempt at learning from teachers
themselves about the circumstances behind their employment,
benefits and working conditions, will greatly aid the government
in adequately funding its education programs and addressing the
concerns and problems of the country's public school tutors,"
Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is called the Teacher Assistance for Optimum
Well-Being, is spearheaded by the Senate Committee on Education,
Arts and Culture chaired by Senator Tessie Oreta.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the findings of the project, Estrada immediately
ordered the Presidential Management Staff and the Housing and
Urban Development Coordinating Council to prepare a proposal for a
teachers' housing program.
</P>
<P>
The president also directed the Technical Education and Skills
Development Authority to provide non-formal training programs for
the unemployed spouses of school teachers "so that we can harness
them for productive purposes."
</P>
<P>
A government report said that about 26 percent of the total
number of teacher-respondents in the research have unemployed
spouses. The report also showed that female teachers with
unemployed husbands outnumber male teachers with unemployed wives.
</P>
<P>
The president also directed Education Department to come up
with a clear proposal on how to compensate teachers assigned to
difficult posts in remote areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
