<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher on
Singapore Stock Market Wednesday with technology stocks taking
centrestage.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) ended today's session
at 2,305.72 points, rising 46.22 points to pierce through the
psychologically-important level of 2,300 points.
</P>
<P>
The turnover totaled 460.51 million units worth 889.69 million
Singapore dollars (526.85 million U.S. dollars). Declining issues
outnumbered advancers by 174 to 140 with 1987 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
I-Comm, a phone-equipment maker, topped the volume list as it
registered a turnover of 61.40 million units. OUB DBeCw01 was the
second most heavily-traded stock which had 25.51 million shares
done. Eastgate was the next with 23.82 million counters changing
hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH was the biggest gainer of the day as it soared up 200 cents
to close at 34.70 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 surged up 180 cents
to finish at 34.60 Singapore dollars. DBS and PacCent ran up 130
cents to end at 23.70 and 24.30 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, BMT 100 led losers of the day giving up 60
cents to close at 74.00 Singapore dollars. Chartered shed 40 cents
to finish at 15.40 Singapore dollars. NatElec retreated 25 cents
to end at 8.70 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market focused on the technology stocks
and investors snapped up dot-com and electronic counters after the
debut today of I-Cmm technology.
</P>
<P>
They also said that shares were supported by bargain-hunting in
blue chips SPH and DBS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
