<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government's Shame Campaign Declared  Unconstitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Court of Appeals
Thursday declared unconstitutional the "Spray-Paint Shame Campaign
" initiated by the Department of Interior and Local Governments,
Philippine News Agency (PNA) said.
</P>
<P>
The appellate court also issued a writ of prohibition to
further prevent implementation of the said campaign, which the
Secretary Alfredo Lim has undertaken as part of the government's
intensified drive against illegal drugs, the PNA said.
</P>
<P>
Lim, appointed to be the secretary of the department by
President Joseph Estrada early January, began the shame campaign
last week in Manila by spray painting signs on two houses, an
effort said to kick off the anti-drug drive nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In a 25 page decision, the court said "scarlet letter' drive is
violative of one of the fundamental guarantees established in the
Constitution that all accused shall be presumed innocent until the
contrary is proved.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the appellate court said the appropriate and legal
course of action is to charge, arrest and prosecute suspected drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
The Manila ordinance allowing the spray painting drive "
violates the constitutional guarantee of due process that hears
before it condemns and renders judgment only after trial," the
court decision said.
</P>
<P>
The appellate tribunal further stressed that the constitutional
guarantee of equal protection of the laws is evidently abridged
under the Manila ordinance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
