<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lifts Duty on Egyptian Rice for Tea Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
lifted tariff on Egyptian rice and wheat flour temporarily to
avert Egyptian boycott of Kenyan tea in a deepening trade crisis,
the East African Standard newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The measure is temporary as the two countries are discussing
how to resolve the trade dispute, Kenyan Finance Minister Chris
Okemo said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A Kenyan trade delegation is currently in Egypt to negotiate
the export- import modalities and a concrete trade agreement is
expected to reach, the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The dispute, which first flared up last November but appeared
to have been resolved last month, was triggered off by Kenya's
unwillingness to reduce tariffs on certain Egyptian exports as
required by the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) pact.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Egypt impounded more than 20 million U.S.
dollars of Kenyan tea at an Egyptian port.
</P>
<P>
Buying over 150 million dollars of Kenyan tea in 1999, Egypt is
the third biggest Kenyan tea buyer only after Britain and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, Egyptian tea buyers boycotted Kenya's weekly
tea auction in Kenya's Indian Ocean port city of Mombasa and sent
the tea prices in the market plunging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Hopeful of IMF Aid Resumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya does not anticipate more
conditionalities by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
World Bank in the newly designed poverty reduction and growth
facility, Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo has said.
</P>
<P>
Okemo made the remarks Wednesday during the signing of exchange
notes with Japanese ambassador to Kenya for the
802-million-shilling (around 11 million U.S. dollars) grant to the
country for immunization programs and the purchase of farm inputs.
</P>
<P>
The minister said most of the conditions set by the IMF after
it suspended the 205-million-dollar loan in 1997 had been met,
with some still being worked on.
</P>
<P>
Okemo noted that these conditionalities should not be seen as
some form of punishment coming from the donor community, but
should be viewed as conditions good for the development of the
country.
</P>
<P>
A visiting IMF team, which arrived here Monday, is now holding
discussions with the government officials, stakeholders and
relevant sectors on the possibilities of the resumption of aid to
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The minister said discussions with the IMF team were very
cordial, but it was not easy to fully comment on what has
transpired.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended the loan to Kenya three years ago for the
alleged poor governance and corruption among other issues in the
east African country. The suspension has brought Kenya's economy
into serious drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
But earlier this month when media reports said that the IMF and
the Kenyan government would resume aid talks soon, the local
currency appreciated quite a lot, from some 74 shillings to one
U.S. dollar late last year to 67 shillings to one dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Mine Deal Stalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Anglo American Corporation has
deferred scheduled signing of the final take-over agreement of
Zambia's copper mines, citing administrative and legal hitches as
the reason, a Zambian newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American acting managing director for central Africa,
Ronnie Peiris, confirmed this Wednesday. But he declined to
disclose the details, saying that the deal will be sealed at a
later date to be announced.
</P>
<P>
It is likely that the closing of the deal will not be achieved
by January 31 this year because of the complex nature of some
legal binding documents, Peiris was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"There are large volumes of the administrative and legal issues
that need to be worked through," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambian Mines Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye said the
deadline could be rescheduled to a later date as it is a mere
guideline. But that does not mean the transaction has failed, the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed last month, the assets of three mines
of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines -- Nchanga Division,
Konkola Division and Nampundwe Mine -- will be sold to Anglo
American.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has been making efforts in recent years
to privatize the southern African country's copper mines in order
to attract foreign investment and advanced technology and
management as soon as possible to revive the ailing mining
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
