<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Ghana to Launch Free Trade Area by April 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Ghana have fixed
April 30 this year as the date for the establishment of a free
trade area between them and several neighbors under the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
A Ghana-Nigeria strategic cooperation meeting has agreed to
implement concrete physical infrastructural projects and programs
to further enhance the integration process, the Guardian newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The customs, national standards organizations and food and
drugs agencies were also urged to work out appropriate modalities
to facilitate the establishment of a free trade area by April 30
this year.
</P>
<P>
A joint meeting of trade ministers of Nigeria and Ghana has
been proposed for February 4 to appraise the status of free trade
area protocols, according to a communique released by the ECOWAS
Secretariat in Abuja Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have now resolved to carry along their neighbors
- Benin and Togo, in the new drive of operating an ECOWAS
borderless zone.
</P>
<P>
The final communique of the Ghana-Nigeria strategic cooperation
meeting said that the four neighboring countries are to embark on
complete eradication of rigid border formalities, the application
of prescribed ECOWAS customs and immigration procedures as well as
the implementation of joint border patrols.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted that a convergence criteria already
approved by the Authority of Heads of State at the 22nd ECOWAS
summit in Togolese capital Lome late last year has also been
adopted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
