<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Economic Performance to Improve: ECA Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The economic performance in
southern Africa is expected to improve this year, a senior
official of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa
(ECA) has predicted.
</P>
<P>
The turn-around in the prices of minerals, particularly copper,
gold and diamonds, is expected to sustain the economies of
southern African countries in the high gear and ensure greater
vibrancy during the year 2000, said Robert Okello, Director of the
ECA Sub-Regional Development Center for Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Given the improved weather conditions registered late 1999, the
outlook of agricultural production in most countries of the
sub-region is bright, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported
Thursday quoted Okello as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, all member countries of the sub-region are targeting
sound macro-economic environment as a fundamental requirement that
would underpin future investment and growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most southern African countries are committed to
continuing the implementation of economic reform programs and
deepening market-based policies in the year 2000, the ECA official
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Okello, regional cooperation and economic
integration will continue to be consolidated in the sub-region,
which will create a large, economically viable and unified market.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
