<HEADLINE> Nigerian Violence Probe Team Starts Working </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's House of
Representatives Committee on the Oodua Peoples Congress (OPC)
violence has begun a fact- finding mission in Lagos, the Guardian
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The OPC is a radical ethnic group of the Yorubas, one of the
Nigeria's three largest nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the 14-member House committee, Malam Zailaini, said
here Wednesday that his team would contact people with diverse
opinions on the OPC issue.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Governor Bola Tinubu, the committee described
the activities of various militant groups in the most populous
African country as capable of tearing the nation apart.
</P>
<P>
Tinubu said that no governor would fold his arms and allow his
state to be taken over by hoodlums.
</P>
<P>
The committee should get to the root of the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, some House representatives asked the federal
government to ban the radical ethnic groups including the OPC and
Arewa Peoples Congress (APC), which were believed to be behind the
recent ethinic conflicts in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between Yorubas, Hausas and Ijaws, other two
major ethnic groups in the west African country, had killed
hundreds of people in recent months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
