<HEADLINE> Cuban Grandmothers Meet Grandson in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The six-year-old Cuban boy,
Elian Gonzalez, was reunited with his grandmothers at Miami Beach
on Wednesday, the United States, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reunion lasted about two hours at the home of Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin, president of Barry University, who has a long history
of helping immigrants, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Mariela Quintana and Raquel Rodriguez, who flew from Cuba last
week with a hope to take Elian back, finally met their grandson,
who was rescued from a shipwreck after his mother and stepfather
drowned when their boat capsized in an effort to come to the
United States illegally.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the grandmothers were received with
tossing flowers when the car came to the nun's house and about 200
demonstrators were waiting outside the house. Some cheered and
others booed as the grandmothers passed.
</P>
<P>
After failing to meet the boy when they flew to Miami on Monday,
the grandmothers asked to meet the boy in a neutral site where
there are no anti-Cuba protesters who demand the boy stay in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of Elian in Florida insist that the boy should stay
with them while the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service (
INS) ruled early this month that the boy belongs to his father in
Cuba and should be returned.
</P>
<P>
Several congressmen and anti-Cuban organizations in the U.S.,
trying to use the boy to attack the Cuban government, appealed for
a citizenship for the boy although it was rejected by his father.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on Wednesday that
he has no solid plans for handling legislation next week to give
Elian U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"Legislation was introduced with regard to the Elian Gonzalez
matter. It is not going to be acted on this week, obviously. It
could come up next week. But there are a lot of people looking at
this issue, and there may be developments between now and then,"
Lott said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton had appealed that politics should be
avoided in handling the Elian case and expressed his support for
the INS decision to return the boy to Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
