<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Presidential Contenders Hold Debates Before Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Republican and Democratic
presidential contenders held their last campaign debates
respectively in New Hampshire Wednesday before the first primary
in the state.
</P>
<P>
In the 90-minute debate, the five Republican contenders covered
topics from education, the price of home heating oil, to campaign
finance.
</P>
<P>
Both Texas Governor George W. Bush and Senator John McCain were
very careful on the issue of abortion, a sensitive topic for the
conservative party.
</P>
<P>
Bush said the Republican Party "must be big enough to welcome"
dissenting views, and the Arizona senator declined to repeat
earlier comments suggesting he might permit his own child to end a
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Bush, whose campaign is based on a theme of "compassionate
conservatism," is hoping to avoid offending moderate voters who do
not agree with the Republican's strong anti-abortion platform.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor is the national front-runner in the
presidential campaign, but McCain leads in most of the pre-primary
polls in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
The Republican field became smaller after Senator Orrin Hatch
from Utah dropped out of the race earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Millionaire publisher Steve Forbes, former ambassador to the U.
N. Alan Keyes and former Reagan aide Gary Bauer also attended the
debate.
</P>
<P>
Later in the evening, Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley took
their turn for the debate at the same location -- a television
studio in New Hampshire's largest city with no live audience.
</P>
<P>
Former New Jersey Senator Bradley attacked Vice President Gore
in unusually personal terms in the debate.
</P>
<P>
"When Al accuses me of negative campaigning, that reminds me of
the story about Richard Nixon, the kind of politician who would
chop down a tree, then stand on the stump and give a speech about
conservation," said Bradley, Gore's only contender for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
"If you're going to talk about a higher standard you're going
to need to live by them," Gore rebutted.
</P>
<P>
The two men also clashed sharply about negative campaign
advertising.
</P>
<P>
The 60-minute debate marked an abrupt change in campaign
tactics by Bradley, observers said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first debate since Gore's runaway victory in Iowa
caucuses and also the final time before New Hampshire holds the
first primary next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Recent polls show that support rates are almost the same for
the two rivals, but victory is more important politically for
Bradley, given his poor showing in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
Both Gore and Bradley are battling for independents who could
prove decisive in the primary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
