<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Rising in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in
Tokyo for the second straight day Thursday, led mainly by
information and technology issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 98.53 points, or 0.52
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 19,209.72.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 21.81 points or 1.31 percent to 1,685.
90.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up slightly to 567.17
million shares from Wednesday's 547.58 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Electric was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said fears about the yen's further rise have receded,
leading export-oriented high-tech issues higher, after monetary
officials from the Group of Seven economic powers last Saturday in
Tokyo voiced shared concern about the yen's appreciation.
</P>
<P>
High-tech issues were firm, despite Wednesday's decline in the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index in New York.
</P>
<P>
Semiconductor-related issues also remained strong, but estate
firms faced selling following their gains the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 814 to 413 despite the rises in the Nikkei and the TOPIX,
with 116 issues closing unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
