<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Expresses Great Concern to Austria on Extreme Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- France Thursday again expressed
its great concern over a possible entry into the government by
Austria's extreme-right.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac called his Austrian counterpart,
Thomas Klest, to seek information on the situation in Austria and
to express his concern.
</P>
<P>
"As a partner of the European Union, and without any intention
of interference, he (Chirac) expressed his great concern about the
way in which the political situation is evolving in Austria," said
the spokeswoman of Elysee presidential palace Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said in an interview with
the Swedish television in Stockholm that a coming to power by the
extreme right would be a "disturbing event" for France.
</P>
<P>
Jospin also said that he would coordinate with other European
Union countries on how to react to the situation.
</P>
<P>
After the Social-Democrat Chancellor Viktor Klima gave up his
effort to form a government, Austria's right-wing and extreme-
right parties are negotiating on the formation of a coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
