<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Closes 648 Small Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province, a major coal-
consumer in northwest China, closed down 648 small coal mines and
cut coal production by about 4.63 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The closings were a part of China's efforts to curb the random
development of small coal mines and save resources, reduce coal
mine accidents, and improve the environment.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to this streamlining, the province's coal production is
now in good order, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Gansu had 1,300 small coal mines run by township enterprises or
state firms at the beginning of 1999, and blind production by
these mines had led to an oversupply of coal and a price war on
the local market, posing a serious threat to the normal operations
of state-run coal mines.
</P>
<P>
In addition, these mines caused heavy pollution and were the
site of frequent accidents, mainly due to poor equipment.
</P>
<P>
To reduce huge coal stockpiles, the provincial government sent
more than 1,200 inspectors to the small mines to supervise their
reduction and closing.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have paid off, as pollution has been reduced and
productivity improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Yuanmou Fossil Evidence Promotes Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 27 (Xinhua)-- The fossilized lower-jaw of a
Yuanmou Man, believed to be the origin of man in China, has been
discovered in Yunnan Province in southwest China, and is
considered a breakthrough for China's palaeoanthropological
research.
</P>
<P>
From study of the camber of the intact lower jaw much can be
learned about the evolution process of the ape-man genus,
according to Qi Guoqin, a specialist in the study of ancient
vertebrates and palaeoanthropology at the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The first Yuanmou Man, which dates back to around 1.7 million
years ago, was discovered in 1965 at Shangnabang Village in
Yuanmou County, Yunnan Province. The first finds were two fossil
teeth, which were identified as human central upper incisors
belonging to one adult. After that, a lower jaw fossil was
discovered in 1984, regarded as a key piece of evidence on the
evolution of China's pithecanthropus.
</P>
<P>
China set up a national research program including a probe into
whether or not China is the origin of human beings. In addition to
the discovery of the lower jaw of Yuanmou Man, more than 80 ape-
men teeth, and over one thousand fossils of various species of
ancient animals were also unearthed by experts involved in the
program.
</P>
<P>
All these fossils make up an ecological group that, to some
extent, show the ancient climate, ecology, geography and even
relationships between ape-men and animals, said Qi.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is abundant in various pithecanthropus fossils, and one
Australian paleoanthropologist said he believes many more finds
could be made there if the same amount of manpower and materials
were used as that employed at some sites in Africa.
</P>
<P>
A further excavation project is currently underway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi to Build More High-Tech Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region will make greater efforts to build more high-
tech development zones in the future.
</P>
<P>
In the years to come, high and new technologies, as well as the
industries based on them should play a more important role in
advancing Guangxi's regional economic development, said Li
Zhaozhuo, chairman of the regional government, in his address to a
recent regional meeting on high technology.
</P>
<P>
He urged relevant departments at all levels to turn high-tech
development zones into a new and important economic powerhouse,
and give greater priority to industrial planning in the zones,
attract more high-tech businesses by introducing more foreign
investment, and cultivate a good environment to attract qualified
professionals.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has created three high-tech such zones in Nanning,
Liuzhou, and Guilin, where 1,300 firms are now operating with 50,
000 employees. Among these firms, 240 are high-tech ventures with
30,000 employees, and are capable of producing 500 kinds of high-
tech commodities. 
</P>
