<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Continues to Lure Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal
government will make more efforts to attract foreign investment
for economic development in the Chinese capital this year, with
focus placed on funds from multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
New measures, including opening Internet web site and inviting
overseas intermediary institutions for business promotion, will be
adopted to lure foreign investors, said Vice-Mayor Zhang Mao at a
work conference on foreign trade and economic cooperation today.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to attract funds from Asian countries and
regions, the city will pay special attention to encouraging
investors from the European Union and North America, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the city will encourage multinational corporations
to set up their regional headquarters in Beijing, open its market
wider to the outside world, and give strong support for
cooperation between local state-owned enterprises and
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 154 of the world's top 500 transnational
corporations have invested in Beijing, including Microsoft, Lucent,
Bell, Siemens, Ericsson, Epson, Matsushita, and Philips. Last year,
altogether 258 foreign-invested ventures in the city increased
their investments by more than one billion U.S. dollars to expand
operations.  
</P>
