<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rat Poison Kills Birds in Ancient Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The staff at the Temple of
Confucius in Beijing are astonished that the poison they prepared
for rats and pests has killed birds inhabiting the temple.
</P>
<P>
Li Chaoying, chief of the protection administration of the
temple, said, "In the past three years, there have been three or
four dead owls and magpies around here each year, and tests show
they had eaten poisoned dead rats or poison bait."
</P>
<P>
The staff at the temple, where stand more than 100 cypress
trees and ancient architecture, had used pesticide and rat poison
to kill spider mites and rats in the temple in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Located in eastern Beijing, the Temple of Confucius used to be
where emperors in feudal dynasties did obeisance to Confucius (
551 B.C. - 479 B.C.), China's great philosopher and educator. Now
the temple accommodates tens of thousands of visitors from China
and abroad, as well as hundreds of owls, cuckoos and magpies which
build nests on the trees and sometimes stay around all year.
</P>
<P>
Although Beijing is now in winter, with daytime temperature
about three Centigrade below zero, dozens of owls can still be
seen flying about and into the old cypress trees at the temple.
</P>
<P>
Li said that when the staff used poison to kill rats, they have
never thought this would be fatal to the birds, adding that this
lesson will make him reconsider ways to protect the temple.
</P>
<P>
Gao Wu, an ornithologist at Capital Normal University, said
after examining the dead birds that it is not a good idea to kill
rats with chemicals which are also harmful to other creatures
living at the temple.
</P>
<P>
Sun Xin of the Beijing Forestry Bureau suggests that old-
fashioned mechanical traps could be used to catch the rats, and
this would be better for the environment.
</P>
<P>
Li said he will submit a report to the authorities and pledged
to solve the problem as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
