<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stock Market Expands Further in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's stock market has
expanded further in 1999, with the turnover on the Shanghai and
Shenzhen bourses hitting 3.13 trillion yuan, up 33 percent from
1998, said Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the China Securities
Regulatory Commission (CSRC).
</P>
<P>
Zhou said at an ongoing conference here that the number of
China's publicly-listed firms rose to 949 by the end of 1999, and
the market value of their stocks was worth of 2.65 trillion yuan,
up 36 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
Newly-listed firms raised a total of 124.3 billion yuan from
both home and overseas markets in 1999, which is 30 percent higher
than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, investors opened 44.71 million accounts on
the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 saw the most intensive and extensive reforms in
history, resulting in an improved regulatory system, a market-
oriented appraisal system for initial public offering and expanded
capital supply to the market, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies were granted to high-tech enterprises in
1999. Such enterprises now account for 17 percent of the listed
firms in China.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the watchdog to rectify the market order also paid
off, Zhou said. Illegal trading floors were closed down, and a
number of old investment funds have been restructured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Create Markets for High-tech Securities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China will set up markets for
high-tech securities on the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges
this year in support of the development of high-tech enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC) made this remark at an ongoing conference in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, these high-tech markets will have their own
stock indices.
</P>
<P>
The quota system for initial public offerings (IPO) will be
abandoned and replaced by a system under which the chief
underwriters will take more responsibility, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it remains the government's policy to encourage
enterprises going public to raise funds in order to promote state-
owned enterprise (SOEs) reform and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, although all kinds of enterprises will be
allowed to issue stock as long as they meet the required
conditions, yet, priority will be given to SOEs.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government intends to encourage mergers and
takeovers among listed firms as a way to improve their performance.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he acknowledged that the government is considering
exit mechanisms for listed firms that have been losing money for
three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The unsatisfactory performance of some listed firms has become
a major topic of concern among both economists and investors in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
