<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Reinsurance Market Faces Imminent Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China's reinsurance market is
gearing up for competition as the government moves to approve new
reinsurance firms this year in preparation for its expected entry
into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Currently, the reinsurance market is monopolized by the China
Reinsurance Company (China Re), which was formed four years ago
and split from the former People's Insurance Company of China (
group) in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Dai Fengju, China Re's general manager, said his company is not
afraid of competition from either at home or abroad.
</P>
<P>
China Re, as the first-comer, has many advantages, he said,
noting that in its fours years of operation, the company has
accumulated experience, fostered a batch of top-level managers and
technicians, and gathered influence that could be daunting to
potential competitors.
</P>
<P>
The company reported a premium income of 11.8 billion yuan (1.4
billion US dollars) in 1998 and nine billion yuan (10.8 billion US
dollars) in the first nine months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Its assets have increased from the initial three billion yuan (
361 million US dollars) to the present 11.5 billion yuan (1.4
billion US dollars), and its liability reserve from 4.8 billion
yuan (578 million US dollars) to eight billion yuan (964 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The entrance of foreign business rivals would bring competition
as well as advanced management and technology, which would compel
China Re to further improve its management and service, Dai added.
</P>
<P>
Not only will competitors from home and abroad seek their share
of the market, Dai said, but all firms will be working hard to
find qualified reinsurance professionals, and China already has an
acute shortage of those.
</P>
<P>
As a state-owned enterprise (SOE), China Re faces the same
problems in corporate governance and management as other SOEs, Dai
said. So the company would strive to transform itself into a
modern enterprise and internationally-competitive reinsurer in
three years.
</P>
<P>
This year, the company will reform its major departments so as
to clarify the rights and responsibilities of each position and
pay each employee according to performance.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Dai said, an experimental reform has taken place in
its Property Insurance Department in 1999, producing a 60 percent
rise in its domestic commercial reinsurance business volume.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after it became an independent operator last year, the
company set its goal of becoming one of the top 10 reinsurers in
the world both in premium income and management in 10 years. Dai
said the goal remains unchanged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
