<HEADLINE> China, Cuba Sign WTO Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China and Cuba signed a
bilateral agreement on China's entry to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) here today.
</P>
<P>
China's Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (
MOFTEC) Shi Guangsheng and Cuban Minister of Foreign Trade Ricardo
Cabrisas Ruiz signed the agreement on behalf of their respective
governments.
</P>
<P>
Shi described the bilateral agreement as an important document
that will help deepen the bilateral relations as well as the
economic and trade relations between China and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
It will help accelerate the process of China's entry to the WTO
and China is grateful to the Cuban Government for its long-term
and firm support for China's WTO entry, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's bid to enter the WTO has lasted 14 years. It reached
agreement with the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral talks with the EU this week in Brussels resulted in
progress, and China is ready to sign bilateral agreements with
other WTO members one by one in the coming few months, Shi told
reporters following the signing of the China-Cuba agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban trade minister said that Cuba and other developing
countries of the world all hope China will join the WTO at the
earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
The WTO is incomplete without the participation of China, he
told Shi.
</P>
<P>
Cabrisas arrived here on Monday for the 12th conference of
China-Cuba Mixed Committee on Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
