<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Salt Well Still Working </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A 160-year-old salt well with a
depth of more than 1,000 meters, believed to be the oldest of its
kind in the world, is still turning out edible salt every day.
</P>
<P>
At present, local workers continue to produce salt with methods
passed down for generations, but production has been only on a
small scale as a demonstration for visitors since the well was
listed as a cultural-relic site.
</P>
<P>
The salt well, called Shenhai, was dug in 1835 in the city of
Zigong in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
"Salt production here involves several processes, which
incorporate the wisdom of salt workers of the past," said one
worker.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, we add some soybean to skim off impurities so
the salt won't be gritty," he added.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that although the salt from the Shenhai well has a
low iodine content, it does contain rich trace elements, and
pickled vegetable made with this salt has a distinctive flavor.
</P>
<P>
The city of Zigong has been turning out salt for 1,900 years,
and it led the world in salt-well mining and salt production for
more than a century, until the end of the Qing Dynasty in 1911.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reduces Winter Crops Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- China reduced the planting area
of winter grain crops by 1.65 million ha last year, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
The National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) released a report here
today saying that the planting area of winter grain crops totaled
27.77 million ha in 1999, a decrease of 5.6 percent from the same
period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Winter wheat saw the largest decrease of planting area over the
past two years, dropping 1.7 million ha, or 6.7 percent over the
previous year, to 23.87 million ha.
</P>
<P>
This decrease was partly due to the continuous drop of grain
prices, as the government stopped paying protective prices for low-
quality crops such as winter wheat.
</P>
<P>
According to the NBS report, grain growers in all 26 wheat-
growing provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have
reduced the planting area of winter wheat.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the planting area of oil seeds surged by 8.7
percent due to rising market prices, and the total planting area
last winter reached 6.89 million ha, increasing 549,000 ha over
the previous winter season.
</P>
<P>
The planting area of vegetables also grew by 594,000 ha, or 11
percent, to 5.98 million ha last winter, while the planting areas
of other grain crops increased from 0.7 percent to 4.03 million ha.
</P>
</TEXT>
