<HEADLINE> Filipinos Urged to Respect Estrada's Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Vice President Gloria
Macapagal-Arroyo urged the people to respect the mandate of
President Joseph Estrada to lead the country until the year 2004,
the national leading newspaper Manila Bulletin said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the vice president rejected calls for snap
election made by some sectors.
</P>
<P>
"We should all respect that mandate," she was quoted as saying
at her weekly press conference at the Philippine International
Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
Macapagal-Arroyo joined President Estrada Wednesday morning in
the 20th National Prayer Breakfast at the Manila Hotel in praying
for national unity.
</P>
<P>
She expressed confidence that Estrada, whose popularity rating
has plunged to alarming levels, will regain his popularity through
his various initiatives aimed at alleviating the plight of the
Filipino masses.
</P>
<P>
In the latest Pulse Asia survey, Macapagal-Arroyo garnered a
net approval rating of 78 percent with the Luzon region giving her
an 80 percent rating, Visayas -- 70 percent and Mindanao -- 86
percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey conducted by the Social Weather
Station, however, Estrada's net approval rating declined
drastically from 28 percent in October 1999 to the all-time low
record of positive five percent in December of the same year.
</P>
