<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Restarts Attempt to Contact Mars Polar Lander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Mission controllers at a
NASA lab started a new attempt on Wednesday to contact the Mars
Polar Lander after they distinguished a weak radio signal which
might have been sent by the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
After a review of data collected by a radio antenna at Stanford
University, mission controllers at NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena said the antenna had possibly heard
something from the Lander during the tests on December 18 or
January 4.
</P>
<P>
The new attempt to contact the Mars Lander was announced by
NASA on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, mission controllers were not optimistic about the new
effort. "This week's test is a real long-shot," said Richard Cook,
the spacecraft's project manager.
</P>
<P>
The Lander was last heard from on December 3 when it was
entering the Martian atmosphere for a 90-day mission to study the
planet's climate and search for frozen water reserve.
</P>
<P>
NASA officially abandoned its efforts to locate the craft on
January 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
