<HEADLINE> Ilgauskas Has Surgery to Repair Broken Left Foot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Already out for the season,
Cleveland Cavaliers center Zydrunas Ilgauskas underwent surgery on
his broken left foot today, beginning the long road back to
possibly playing next season.
</P>
<P>
Ilgauskas, 24, has not played since being diagnosed with the
break on February 17, 1999. The injury forced him to miss the
final 45 game of last season and had not fully healed despite
extended rest and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Ilgauskas participated in training camp in October but had
recurring pain and was placed on the injured list. Following eight
weeks of rest, he returned to limited practice on January 1.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time in his career he has been lost for the
season. A 1996 first-round pick of the Cabaliers, he missed the
1996-97 campaign due to a similar injury in his right foot.
</P>
<P>
The loss of Ilgauskas is a severe blow to the Cavaliers, who
are on the outside looking in at the playoff race with a 17-25
mark.
</P>
<P>
He averaged 15.2 points and 8.8 rebounds before last season's
setback. 
</P>
