<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing to Build War Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chongqing municipal
government has approved the creation of a memorial to commemorate
the bombing of the city by Japanese invaders during the War of
Resistance Against Japan (1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
The project is intended to remind people of the atrocities
committed by the Japanese aggressors, console the souls of Chinese
warriors who died during the war, and educate younger generations,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated by the Chongqing Municipal Committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
and later won support from the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the city established a research center on the
bombing of Chongqing and collected more than 500 relics and
documents related to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Between January 1938 and August 1943, Japan made 6,800 air-
strikes against this southwestern city, killing or injuring more
than 20,000 people and leaving over 60,000 buildings in ruins.
</P>
<P>
With preliminary construction plans adopted and the fund in
place, selection of the memorial site is now underway.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is one of China's exceptionally large cities with a
history of more than 3,000 years. It is the largest economic
center and an important transportation hub in southwestern China
and on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
In 1940, Chongqing was made a "wartime capital" by the
Kuomintang government and was the political, economic, commercial,
financial, transportation, cultural, and diplomatic center of the
country at that time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Municipal Government to Downsize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Municipal People's
Government will cut back its staff by 50 percent in order to
increase efficiency, and the 67 offices under the municipal
government will be reduced to 45.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) will cut down its working departments to 12 from 17, and the
number of employees at the Beijing Municipal Party Committee will
be reduced by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
This organizational restructuring reform plan, mapped out in
accordance with the request of the CPC Central Committee and the
State Council, was just approved by the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the current organizational structure of the
Beijing municipal Party committee and the municipal government are
inefficient and have overlapping functions.
</P>
<P>
The reform is aimed at building a cooperative, simple, and
scientific and efficient operational system. To meet the demands
of developing Beijing's economy and building the city into an
international metropolis, the Beijing municipal government will
establish an administrative management system that accords with
the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The city will carry out this reform plan in the first quarter
this year, and laid-off employees will be reassigned within three
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
