<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up 24 New Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
approved the setting up of 24 factories worth 3,197 million rupees
(45 million U.S. dollars) in three industrial parks in a bid to
further decrease unemployment, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These factories, to be set up at the industrial parks at
Sitawaka, Minuwangoda and Ratnapura, will generate 9,000 direct
and indirect employment opportunities, the state-run Daily News
quoted Industrial Development Minister C.V. Gooneratne as saying.
</P>
<P>
The factories will produce electrical items, go-karts, motor
spares, paints, galvanized products, wheelbarrows, toys, steel
furniture, sports equipment, medical gloves, high quality garment
products and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
The report said that there are in all 21 industrial parks in
the island country aimed at reducing unemployment. Consequently
the unemployment rate which was 13.6 percent in 1994 dropped to 8.
6 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Sitawaka Industrial Park is Sri Lanka's first international
standard industrial park spreading over 168 hectares in suburban
Colombo. It is expected to create over 50,000 direct and indirect
employment opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
