<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel Group Demands Establishment of Demilitarized Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's second
largest guerrilla group, the National Liberation Army (ELN), has
demanded that the government establish a demilitarized zone in the
north of the country to facilitate the relaunch of a balked peace
process, a parliamentary source said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Member of the ELN's central commando, Pablo Beltran, made the
demand at a meeting Tuesday with a Colombian parliamentary
delegation, which acts as mediator to save a preliminary peace
accord signed by the rebel group and Colombia's civil associations
in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which took place in Caracas, capital city
of neighboring Venezuela, Beltran reiterated the need for a
demilitarized zone in a jungle area of Bolivar department, said
senator Carlos Espinosa Faciolince, one of the parliamentary
delegates.
</P>
<P>
The ELN asked for the withdrawal of the military and police
from four townships, among those San Pablo with an area of close
to 6,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary delegation said it was urgent for the
government to decide whether to establish the demilitarized zone
and under what conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
