<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese White Dolphin Fighting Solitude for 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Qiqi jumped out of water, his
silver body making a beautiful arc in the air before diving into
the water to splash sprays as a welcome to the visitors who have
come to see him at his home in a pool by Donghu Lake In Wuhan in
central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Qiqi is a white-finned dolphin, a species unique to China, and
the most endangered dolphin species in the world. Qiqi is the only
one living in captive.
</P>
<P>
Hosting visitors from time to time excites Qiqi. The lonely
male dolphin has survived alone in the 300 sq.m. pool for 20 years,
since he was rescued in 1980 in Dongting Lake near China's longest
river, the Yangtze, which is the species' main habitat.
</P>
<P>
When he was found, Qiqi was a badly bruised two-year-old.
Experts examining him suspected the injuries were caused by
illegal fishing, which has been condemned as one of the main
contributors to the diminishing number of white dolphins in the
wild, from some 400 in the early 1980s to far less than 100 now.
</P>
<P>
The Fishery Bureau of the Chinese Ministry of Agriculture has
warned that the ancient mammal species which has survived 20 to 30
million years of evolution may face extinction within another 25
years unless effective measures are immediately enforced.
</P>
<P>
Qiqi is old now, considering the average life-span of 30 years
for white dolphins. Springtime is still hard for him, as he longs
for a mate. His caretakers worry that disorders resulting from
solitude may be dangerous and cause serious complications.
</P>
<P>
China has tried every means to save the white dolphins. The
Fishery Bureau has carried out a program monitoring Yangtze white-
fin dolphins every November since 1997, the largest such
monitoring program of rare animals in China, with the search
conducted over a 1,900-km-long stretch of the middle and lower
reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
However, only five to seven dolphins have been sighted each
season, even with the use of advanced devices.
</P>
<P>
The white dolphins are still struggling in a deteriorating
environment, in addition to constant life-threatening escapes from
illegal fishermen and the disturbance of the busy waterways of the
Yangtze. Because of these conditions, several of Qiqi's
prospective mates died before ever meeting him.
</P>
<P>
Qiqi might not have survived in his natural habitat. His
present good health is due in part to routine monthly physical
check-ups, and the meticulous care he receives in his artificial
environment, which has cost over 10 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
To sustain the species' longevity, scientists from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences is experimenting cloning a white dolphin.
Zhang Xianfeng, an academician in charge of the project, said
this is theoretically feasible, and his team is creating up a data
bank of white-dolphin cell information in preparations for the
final test.
</P>
<P>
He said that experts from the United States, Germany, and
Switzerland have been ardent in providing their expertise in
support of projects designed to save this severely endangered
species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
