<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Create RNA Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 26 (Xinhua) -- A computer using the
biological molecule RNA to solve complex problems was developed by
a U.S. research team, marking a significant advance in molecular
computing, the Science Daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The computer, developed by Princeton University researchers,
was a test tube containing 1,024 different strands of RNA, a
genetic material.
</P>
<P>
In work to be published in the Proceedings of the National
Academy of Sciences, the scientists used the test-tube computer to
solve a simple version of the "Knight problem," a chess puzzle
that asks how many and where one can place knights on a chessboard
so they cannot attack each other.
</P>
<P>
For their experiment, the researchers restricted the board to
nine squares, leaving 512 possible combinations.
</P>
<P>
Of these, the RNA computer correctly found 43 solutions.
</P>
<P>
The test-tube computer does not have any immediate applications,
and it will probably never completely replace silicon-based
computers, said assistant professor Laura Landweber who led the
research team.
</P>
<P>
However, it does have attractive aspects. One advantage, said
Landweber, is that RNA and another genetic molecule DNA, which
encode all the instructions for creating and running life, can
store much more data in a given space than conventional memory
chips.
</P>
<P>
With vast numbers of genetic fragments of DNA and RNA floating
in a test tube, a biomolecular computer could perform thousands or
millions of calculations at the same time.
</P>
<P>
DNA computing has attracted considerable attention from
researchers since 1994 when Leonard Adleman of the University of
Southern California used DNA to solve a traveling salesman problem.
Some 10 research teams are now engaged in the development of
molecular computing in America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
