<HEADLINE> Mexico, Singapore Register Record Trade Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Mexico and
Singapore reached an unprecedented volume of 1.28 billion U.S.
dollars last year, Singapore's Trade Development Board (TDB) said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries showed an upturn trend, even
though Mexico closed the year with a deficit of 102.3 million
dollars, according to a TDB report available here.
</P>
<P>
The unfavorable balance resulted from Mexico's imports from
Singapore, worth 692 million dollars, surpassing its exports to
that country, worth 589.7 million dollars, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's imports from Singapore rose 37 percent while exports
grew only 10.33 percent in the said year.
</P>
<P>
Mexico became Singapore's largest Latin American trade partner
in the year, as trade between the two countries surpassed the
combined total of Singapore's trade with Brazil, Argentina and
Chile.
</P>
<P>
Last September, during a bilateral meeting within the APEC (
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation) forum in New Zealand,
Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong proposed to Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo the establishment of a free trade
agreement (FTA) between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two governments are scheduled to hold negotiations in March
or April in a bid to reach an accord of investment promotion and
protection, which will lay the basis for an FTA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
