<HEADLINE> Montenegro's Parallel Currency Policy Unconstitutional: Yugoslav Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Constitutional
Court of Yugoslavia ruled on Wednesday that Montenegro violated
the Constitution when it decided last November to use German mark
as a parallel currency with Yugoslav dinar.
</P>
<P>
That decision violates the federal Bank Law and regulations on
foreign currency circulation, the court said.
</P>
<P>
Another decision made by Montenegro, one of the republics of
the Yugoslav Federation, was to let its own people's bank to take
over all local functions of the Yugoslav People's Bank. This was
also unconstitutional, the court said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Montenegro made the decision on November 2 ,1999,
the Yugoslav People's Bank, the country's central bank, requested
the federal constitutional court to render an adjudication on the
issue, saying that Montenegro's decision violated the Constitution
and could create serious problems for the federal monetary and
foreign currency systems.
</P>
<P>
The federal Bank Law prohibits companies operating within
Yugoslavia from doing foreign currency transactions. But
Montenegrin officials said that the parallel currency policy was
designed to protect the economy and the interests of the people
and to avoid hyperinflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
