<HEADLINE> American Countries Discuss Tuna Fishing Quota Revision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen member states of the
Inter-American Tropical Tuna Convention (CIAT) began a meeting
here Wednesday to revise tuna fishing quotas and explore ways to
limit tuna capture in face of the growing capacity of fishing
fleets.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day work meeting, the participants are
expected to propose alternatives on tuna capture limitation and
give advice to next June's CIAT assembly on regulating fishing
operations.
</P>
<P>
CIAT imposed a restriction on the capture of yellow-fin tuna in
1998 and renewed the measure last year, said CIAT director Robin
Allen.
</P>
<P>
Yellow-fin tuna accounts for nearly 60 percent of all tuna
catch every year in the Tropical Eastern Pacific, which extends
from the United States to Chile and represents 40 percent of tuna
capture in the world. 
