<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificial Seawater for Prawn Breeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JI'NAN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Large tracts of saline-alkali
land in China's Yellow River Delta were left barren for ages with
no economic value, until recently.
</P>
<P>
 Scientists are now combining salt water with fresh water to
create an artificial seawater suitable for breeding aquatic
products.
</P>
<P>
 In Kenli County of Shandong Province in east China, farmers,
with the help of scientists, have made use of 21 hectares of
barren land to breed prawns. As a result, each hectare has turned
out 116,500 yuan (about 13,915 U.S. dollars) worth of prawns, 12
times the average level of areas along the coast.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Fazhen, a scientist at the Chinese Academy of Engineering,
said that breeding of prawns in ponds in interior areas can be
made immune to certain infections if they are raised in seawater,
and this will also prevent sea pollution and greatly raise the
unit yield.
</P>
<P>
The county plans to reclaim another 45 hectares of barren land
for prawn breeding to promote local economic development this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
