<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Bailey Returns to Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Olympic 100 meters
champion Donovan Bailey finished only fourth in the 60m at an
indoor meeting in Halle, Germany, on Wednesday in his first
competition after a long absence through injury.
</P>
<P>
Bailey, who aimed to defend his Olympic gold medal in Sydney
this September, finished fourth in 6.65 second.
</P>
<P>
Hungary's Roland Nemeth came first with 6.60 second, 100m world
championship bronze medallist Tony Dees of the United States was
second with 6.63 and Hungary's Gabor Dobos took third spot after
clocking 6.64.
</P>
<P>
Bailey had been off the track for nine months after rupturing
his Achilles tendon playing baseball with friends in September
1998, and only returned in June last year with a poor time at
Nuremburg.
</P>
<P>
He did not win one race in 1999 and his best time over 100m was
10.19 at the Canadian championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
