<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Participation in Multilateral Talks Useless: Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim
Hoss said his country saw no use in participating the multilateral
talks, which are scheduled to resume in Moscow early February.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the multilateral talks committee on refugee
affairs focus only on the refugee humanitarian issues rather than
their return to their homes, Hoss told reporters here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon seeks a final solution to the problem of the Palestinian
refugees under the international laws that provide for their
return, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Lebanon briefed all parties concerned, especially
the U.S., on this position. U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Thomas
Pickering assured Lebanon in a message that peace would not be at
its expense, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli daily Ha'artz said Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat offered the U.S. a plan on the final status talks, in which
he agreed to a settlement with Israel recognizing the
Palestinians' "right to return" with a suspended enforcement. The
settlement means that the refugees would remain where they are.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, which hosts at present a total of 400,000 Palestinian
refugees at 12 camps nationwide, has demanded that Israel agree to
the return of the refugees to their homeland. Israel has repeatedly
rejected the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The multilateral Middle East talks will discuss issues of common
interests including demilitarization, water resources, refugees and
environment protection. 
</P>
<P>
The first multilateral negotiations were convened in Moscow in
January 1992 within the framework of Madrid conference. But the
talks were frozen, together with bilateral negotiations, in early
1996 as the whole peace process came to a halt following a series
of terrorist attacks in Israel carried out by Islamic militants. 
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which boycotted the multilateral talks from
the outset, refused to attend the Moscow talks, saying such
meetings were meaningless if they have not made peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>

</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks that resumed last December have hit a
snag, with the third round of negotiations postponed indefinitely.
On the Palestinian track, the talks on a final peace deal were
sluggish though the February 13 deadline for a framework agreement
on the permanent peace deal is at hand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
