<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Acknowledges Globalization Negative Aspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations acknowledged
that the costs of globalization are bigger than its benefits, said
Oscar de Rojas, general supervisor of the international
organization's Economic and Social Affairs Department, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The globalization increased the marginalization of countries
and persons, the asymetries between the industrialized economies
and those in development, as well as the injustices produced by
this model, said De Rojas before the International Encounter of
Economists in Havana.
</P>
<P>
Rojas said that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan shares the
concerns for the economic development problems within the
globalization.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief told those attending the forum the negotiations
in progress to improve the living standards in the developing
countries and in those less advanced.
</P>
<P>
De Rojas said that the discussion in the U.N. General Assembly
about the feasibility of development in the context of the
globalization started two years ago, while the most developed
countries have been urged to engage in a more effective
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Globalization by itself does not guarantee equality and social
justice, although on the opinion of the U.N. secretary-general it
opens possibilities to promote development in many fields of human
activity, especially for the advance of technology of information
and communications.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 specialists from more than 50 countries and 200 Cuban
delegates and foreign guests take part in the Second International
Encounter of Economists that will end Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
