<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Court Gives Life-Term to Rwanda Genocide Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal on Rwanda (ICTR) sentenced Thursday the former
director of the Rwandan state-owned tea factory to life
imprisonment for his role in the 1994 Rwanda Genocide.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Musema, 51, was found guilty of three counts, genocide,
 extermination and rape, out of nine charges, said sources from
Arusha, in northern Tanzania where the ICTR located.
</P>
<P>
Musema participated and encouraged his employees in attacks
against the ethnic Tutsis, said the court presided by Jude Yakov
Ostrosky, adding that he also incurred individual crimes including
rape.
</P>
<P>
However, Musema pleaded not guilty to all the charges and his
lawyer, Steven Kay, said he will lodge an appeal against the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
The judgement on Musema is the ICTR's seventh since its
creation on November 8, 1994 by the United Nations Security
Council resolution 955 and the first of this new year.
</P>
<P>
Arrested in Switzerland on February 11, 1995, Musema was first
handled by the Judicial authorities of the Swiss military until
the ICTR requested his transfer to the UN detention facilities in
Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Verdicts have already been handed down to six other Rwandan
genocide suspects, including the former Prime minister Jean
Kambanda, who was given a life imprisonment after pleading guilty
to charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has the mandate to try persons suspected to be
responsible for genocide and other serious violations of the
international humanitarian law committed in the territory of
Rwanda between January 1 and December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also has the mandate to try Rwandan citizens responsible
for such violations committed in the territory of neighboring
states during the 100- day massacre which claimed more than
800,000 civilians mostly the ethnic Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 28 indictments against 45
individuals and a total of 38 indicted individuals are in custody.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000127.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
