<HEADLINE> Kenya Gets Grant From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government Thursday
got a grant of 11.6 million U.S. dollars from Japan for
developing food production and immunization programs countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Japanese ambassador Morihisa Aoki and Kenyan Finance Minister
Chris Okemo signed the agreement, media here reported.
</P>
<P>
The food production grant of 6.4 million dollars is to boost
food production through the purchase of fertilizers, equipment
and agricultural chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The immunization project grant under the Ministry of Health,
totalling 5. 2 million dollars, is aimed at reducing the country's
infant mortality and disability caused by polio, whooping cough
and other childhood diseases.
</P>
<P>
The grant will help in buying vaccines and equipment for all
vaccination centres countrywide and strengthen the activities of
the Kenya Expanded Program on Immunization.  According to
Aoki, under the Polio Eradication Initiative covering the July
1999 - July 2002 period, 20 Japan Overseas Cooperation Volunteers
would be sent to Kenya. 
</P>
