<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Police Seize Large Drug Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenya police has seized an
estimated 4. 8 tons of hashish with a street value of more than
13.6 million U.S. dollars in the country's southeastern coast
city of Mombasa, media here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The seizure was the largest drug bust in Mombasa since 20 tons
of hashish was found at the South Coast hamlet of Bodo in 1996,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
The drug was seized at an upmarket four-bedroom house in Nyali
Estate in the north Coast Wednesday, police said, adding that it
is believed that the drug is on its way to Europe, where it sells
at an even higher price.
</P>
<P>
District Commissioner Ole Legei described the seizure as a
break-through in the fight against drug abuse and trafficking in
the country..
</P>
<P>
Mombasa has become one of the most notorious conduits for
illegal drugs from the Middle and Far East due to Kenya's
relatively unguarded borders and the lack of a Coast guard to
monitor the long shoreline.
</P>
<P>
Legei noted the house where the haul was found had been broken
into and it was likely some of the drugs had already found their
way onto the local market.
</P>
<P>
The drug, which looks like chocolate, was packed in 4,800
sachets each of one kilogramme, ready for sale. It had been
packed in cartons with labels stating it was tomato sauce and
other foreign brand food bearing German and United States trade
marks.
</P>
<P>
Legei said no arrests had been made but police had launched a
major investigation to determine the origin and destination of
the drug haul, and appealed to the public, especially people
operating along the shore, to report any suspicious cargo to the
police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
