<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blix Formally Appointed to Lead Iraq Monitoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Thursday afternoon formally appointed Hans Blix, a
former director of the International Atomic Energy Agency, as the
chief inspector of a new disarmament commission for Iraq, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Annan, who is in Moscow on a three-
day visit to Russia, said that the president of the Security
Council for the month of January, Richard Holbrooke, told him in a
letter that Annan's selection of Blix was formally approved  by
the 15-nation body.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to announce that Dr. Blix is appointed as
Executive Chairman of UNMOVIC (the United Nations Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission)," Annan said, "I expect Dr.
Blix to take up his mandated tasks as soon as possible. Dr. Blix's
appointment will formally take effect upon his assumption of
duties."
</P>
<P>
Blix, 71, was travelling in Antarctica Wednesday. He told U.N.
officials that he would hold a news conference in Sweden early
next month when he returns.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Annan nominated Rolf Ekeus, another Sweden
disarmament expert supported by the United States, to the chief
inspector's job. But his nomination was blocked in the Security
Council by Russia and France.
</P>
<P>
Under the cease-fire resolution that ended the Gulf war in
1991, Iraq has to be certified free of all prohibited weapons
systems and the means to reconstruct them before sanctions imposed
in August 1990, after the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, can be lifted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
