<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall In Worries About Higher Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks finished
lower Thursday as investors expected that an increase in interest
rates by the Federal Reserve next week will be the first of
several this year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gave up early gains to close
down 4.97 at 11,028.02. The blue chip index rose as much as 130
points in the session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 5.53 at 1,398.56 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 30.35 at 4,039.56.
</P>
<P>
After a strong rally in the morning session, the market began
to fall as a government report on strong demands for durable goods
in December suggests that the expected rate hike will be the
first of several this year. The Commerce department reported that
orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods rose in
December, last year.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve Board raised rates three times in last year
to ward off inflation. Investors expected the board to raise
rates again at the next meeting on February 1-2 due to the hot
economy.
</P>
<P>
Disappointing earnings reports from some big-name tech
companies also helped the Nasdaq index lower. Dell Computer
reported late Wednesday that it will miss profit expectations this
quarter partly because of slower demands.
</P>
<P>
Qualcomm continued to fall today. The cellular phone chipmaker
said Wednesday its sales will be low this quarter, dragging its
stock prices lower.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.67 at 628.76 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 29.41 at 882.80. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 4.02 at 517.02.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,592 down, 1,465 up and 479
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.114 billion shares from 1.110
billion in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
