<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Mixed Difficulties Stall Peace Process in DRC  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council's special meeting on the peace prospects in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) is drawing to an end Thursday without any
concrete new measures to bolster the frayed cease-fire agreement,
long sought by African leaders to stop the many-sided conflict in
the central African country.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited U.N. peace-keeping operation in DRC is still
yet to be put in place, even though the issue has been under
discussion in the Security Council so many times.
</P>
<P>
However, the 15-nation Security Council said in a presidential
statement adopted Wednesday that it would move quickly to approve
a resolution authoring the deployment of a U.N. military observer
mission in DRC.
</P>
<P>
In an unusual Security Council meeting, which kicked off
Monday, seven African heads of state and foreign ministers from
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) renewed their
commitment to a collapsing Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement that they
signed in July last year. The presidents were from Angola, Namibia,
Zimbabwe, DRC, Rwanda and Uganda, all involved in the conflict,
which broke out in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
The current conflict in DRC, which shares international
borders with nine other countries, is so large and intractable
that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright compared it to "
Africa's first world war."
</P>
<P>
Despite calls by African regional leaders for a quick
deployment of U.N. peace-keepers, and the Security Council's
promise to "act promptly," diplomats here said that the United
States, who holds the Council presidency for the month of January,
was far from approving the deployment pact and even the promised
resolution on the observer force would have to wait about two
weeks until the White House was given a green light by a reluctant
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The African presidents were invited to the U.N. Headquarters in
New York by Richard Holbrooke, but he told the press here that he
did not expect immediate results.
</P>
<P>
In fact, while the Security Council has been blaming
belligerents in DRC for its inability to authorize the deployment
of U.N. peace-keepers, the participating African leaders
criticized the U.N. body for not showing adequate support for the
peace process in the largest central African country, formerly
known as Zaire.
</P>
<P>
International assistance, including prompt and necessary U.N.
action, is badly needed to put an end to the DRC conflict, which
has largely affected the stability in the Great Lake region and
even Africa as a whole, but warring parties themselves bear
primary responsibility for adhering to commitments and creating
conditions conducive to progress in the much-stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The DRC war is complicated, so are the difficulties in
bringing peace to the African country.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the lack of necessary resources on the ground,
there is distrust among warring parties. Rwanda, together with
Uganda, supported rebels in fighting against DRC President Laurent
Kabila, backed by Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the painstaking mediation efforts by African
countries and the international community, warring parties signed
the Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement. Since then, however, there have
been many cease-fire violations.
</P>
<P>
According to the Calendar for the implementation of the peace
accord, which the warring parties all had agreed upon, most of the
activities should have been completed by this time, including the
inter-Congolese national dialogue, the establishment of new
institutions, exchange of prisoners and disarmament of armed
groups.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the deployment of the U.N. peace-keepers
would long have begun and the orderly withdrawal of foreign troops
from DRC would be in the final stages of completion.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which would pay one-third the cost of a new
mission, insists that the budget be clear and the soldiers'
mandate well defined. Washington is hesitating on the deployment
decision as long as the conflict persists in DRC.
</P>
<P>
But several African presidents said that there can't be peace
without more U.N. help.
</P>
<P>
Time is of an essence at this stage as far as the DRC conflict
is concerned. It is largely accepted that any delay in U.N. action
would further worsen the situation, which has already been a grave
concern for the international community, in the war-torn African
nation.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, to free the DRC people from the war sufferings and
bring peace to the country remains a serious challenge confronting
the international community, especially the Security Council,
which, under the U.N. Charter, has the primary responsibility for
the maintenance of peace and security in the world at large.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations should throw in the necessary financial and
human resources as soon as possible to resolve the DRC conflict,
so as to avoid paying even higher price in the future. This is
crucial under the current circumstances and will be a critical
test of the Security Council's political will and determination in
this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
